<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Producer Prices Drops for 5th Straight Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The producer prices in the U.S.
declined by a seasonally adjusted 0.3 percent in May, the fifth
consecutive month, U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The drop in U.S. Producer Price Index (PPI) in May followed a
0.6 percent decrease in April and marked the first time since the
gauge has declined for five months in a row in 1952.
</P>
<P>
For the year so far, U.S. producer prices have been falling at
an annual rate of 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The drop of PPI in May was led by a 2.1 percent fall in energy
prices, also the fifth in a row, followed a 2.6 percent decrease
in April. And decreasing energy prices also helped offset a 0.4
percent rise in food prices.
</P>
<P>
The so-called core prices -- excluding the volatile food and
energy sectors -- also declined by 0.3 percent, the largest
decrease since October 1994, resulting from price drops for autos
and trucks and computers.
</P>
<P>
Today's report was the latest evidence that inflation pressures
in the U.S. are scarcely to be found in goods-producing industries
and offered more support for a record-setting rally in the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
That offers some reassurance to economists and markets that
torrid economic growth in the first three months of the year, the
fastest in a decade, has moderated.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserver (Fed) will hold a policy-making
meeting July 1-2 and some analysts now predict that the Fed may
not raise the interest rate as the economy is slowing down with
little inflation presure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
