<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Business Inventories Up 0.3 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. business inventories
increased by 0.3 percent in April after a revised 0.2 percent gain
in March, The U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that auto inventories were up by 1.2 percent in
the month following a 0.2 percent gain in March. Excluding autos,
retail inventories increased by 0.6 percent in April following a
decline of 0.3 percent the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing inventories rose by 0.6 percent in April after
rising 0.2 percent a month earlier. And wholesale inventories fell
0.7 percent during April after rising 0.5 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department said that business sales also rose by
0.3 percent in April after falling 0.2 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
That was a sign of stability. If inventories were failing to
keep up with sales, it could be an inflation signal.
</P>
<P>
The combination of inventories and sales produced an
inventories-to-sales ratio of 1.37 in April, the same as in March.
It means that it would take 1.37 months to exhaust the backlog at
the April sales pace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
