<HEADLINE> Mandela Appeals to Address Plight of Exiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has appealled to the business community to make
contributions to assist former exiled youths who are unemployed
and not elegible for special struggle pensions, said a source
here today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement by the President's Office in Cape Town,
Mandela, who has taken the plight of South Africa's children into
heart and set up a special fund for them, had raised the
condition of former exiled youths in his recent talks with
business leaders.
</P>
<P>
"This should be a matter of serious concern to society as a
whole: to ensure that these young patriots are fully integrated
into society and themselves have a stake in ensuring that South
Africa succeeds in building a better life for all," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
A leader of one large corporation, requested that the name of
the company should not be made public for the moment, had pledged
one million Rand (about 225000 US Dollar) to help the President
in this endeavour.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had asked Acting African National Congress
Secretary-General Cheryl Carolus to consult with organisations to
begin the process of establishing appropriate structures,
identifying the individuals concerned and the projects that would
need to be undertaken, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"The President is confident that this small and humble step
will go some way in addressing one of the peculiar social
problems facing our society," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
