<HEADLINE> U.S. Proposal on Fish Thrown Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States today lost its
proposal to have a working group on marine fish species
established at the ongoing conference of the Convention on
International Trade in Endagered Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
In a closely contested election, the U.S. lost by 49 to 50
votes with most countries saying it was premature to establish
the working group.
</P>
<P>
The working group, which would have been responsible for
marine fish and invertebrate species subject to international
trade, would have included small and large fishing nations that
were parties to the CITES, the Food and Agriculture Organisation
(FAO), regional fisheries management and conservation
organisations to champion issues concerning marine fishing.
</P>
<P>
Hiromisa Isa, who headed the Japanese delegation on marine
fisheries, said, "it's premature and unnecessary to establish the
working group now because that is already being looked after by
FAO and not CITES." 
</P>
</TEXT>
