<HEADLINE> Irish President on New Job as U.N. Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Irish President Mary Robinson, who
has been appointed as United Nations Commissioner for Human
Rights, said today in Dublin that she would build bridges between
developing and developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Robinson, who has decided not to run for a second term when her
presidency expires later this year, told a Dublin gathering that
"It is a daunting task to take on principal responsibility for
human rights on behalf of the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
She said her new job would require a new understanding between
the world's rich and poor countries.
</P>
<P>
"There will need to be bridges built between developing
countries and the developed world, a need to listen and a need to
stand up at times with courage," she said. 
</P>
