<HEADLINE> Cook Calls Hong Kong a Bridge Between China and Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook says Hong Kong should be a bridge and not a barrier between
Britain and China after its return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
With only 17 days left for Hong Kong's return to China, Cook,
in his article carried in The Times newspaper today, said the
return of Hong Kong to China "marks no end of Britain's engagement
with Hong Kong and China, but a new beginning."
</P>
<P>
"I have made it clear that Hong Kong should be a bridge, not a
barrier, between Britain and China. A stable and prosperous Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region would then be at the center of
a more constructive relationship with China," said Cook, who is to
accompany Prince Charles and Prime Minister Tony Blair to Hong
Kong for the return ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"We saw a successful transition of Hong Kong, on the basis of
the Sino-British Joint Declaration of 1984, as one of our highest
priorities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cook stressed that Britain has substantial economic interests
in Hong Kong and China's inland areas which the new Labor
government is pledged to promote.
</P>
<P>
"It is both in Britain's and China's interests that Hong Kong
should remain prosperous," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
