<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Supports Controlled Trade in Rhino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa today voiced support
for a strictly controlled legal trade in rhino horn and other
products saying that would reduce illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
George Hughes, chief executive of the natal parks board in the
South African province of Kwazulu-Natal, gave a lengthy
presentation at the ongoing 10th conference of the CITES in
Harare, arguing that the availability of a legal source of rhino
horn would provide a strong disincentive to consumers to purchase
horn on the black market.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which has a southern white rhino population of
between 7,200 and 7,500, is proposing that restrictions
preventing international trade in rhino and other products be
lifted.
</P>
<P>
He said the trade ban had not been effective in providing
protection for rhinos.
</P>
<P>
He added only those populations that have been effectively
protected and managed have maintained their numbers or increased.
</P>
<P>
But, the International Environmental Investigation Agency
(EIA) has called for the outright rejection of the proposal by
South Africa, saying it would have a number of negative
consequences, including directly threatening all other species of
rhino both in Africa and Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Approves Multimedia Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The lower house of the German
parliament, the Bundestag, today approved a controversial
multimedia law designed to govern commercial on-line services
through the international computer network Internet.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians of the Bonn's ruling parties said the law
would provide a useful legal tool to strengthen data protection
and block the distribution of pornography and material that
glorifies violence over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
What is unique internationally is that the law would provide
protection for the so-called digital signature to ensure personal
identities vital for on-line services like home-banking and
home-shopping.
</P>
<P>
Private certification units under state supervision would be
charged with the tasks to prove the genuineness of the digital
seals on demand.
</P>
<P>
The law also makes it more clear who is legally liable when
forbidden material, like pornography or propaganda provoking
ethnic hatred, becomes available over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, Internet services providers will shoulder full
responsibility for the content of their own services. And if their
services were used by customers to provides the forbidden
material, the providers would only be held responsible when they
know the content in advance and do nothing to block the material
when it is technically possible.
</P>
<P>
Parliament members of the main opposition in Bonn, the Social
Democratic Party (SPD), abstained from voting on the law, saying
that it is not powerful enough to put private enterprises under
control. Another opposition party, the Greens, voted against the
law, saying that it would undermine the international
competitiveness of German enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The law also faces strong opposition from German Internet
services providers who warn that the legislation could put their
business in even greater legal danger and force them to move their
operations to other countries.
</P>
<P>
The multimedia law is still scheduled to be voted on July 4 in
the Bundesrat, the upper house of the German parliament, where the
SPD controls a majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
