<HEADLINE> Attack and Capture of Towns Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Somali factions have expressed
mixed reactions over yesterday's invasion by Ethiopian forces
in the border region of Gedom.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Hussein Mohamed Aidid's government has
condemned the attack and the capture of Luq and Bulo Hawo towns
today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Mr Abikar Sheikh Hussein Qallim has
characterized the invasion as intolerable and a deliberate
violation on the territorial integrity of Somalia. Mr Qalli has
called the United Nations and the JOAU to take the necessary
actions against the Ethiopian aggression.
</P>
<P>
In a different statement, the deputy chairman of Ali Mahdi's
faction has ruled out any foreign involvement in the Gedo region
affairs. Dr Hussein Haji Ahmed Bod said the fighting has occurred
between the forces of Al-Itihad and the local militiamen loyal to
the Somali National Front (SNF) belonging to Marehan clan.
</P>
<P>
Dr Dob has faulted the Al-Itihad Al-Islam for distabilizing
Gedo region and displacing many civilians. He also said that
there are foreign Muslim militants accompanying the Al-Itihad men
in what he called the distabilization of the region.
</P>
<P>
However, initial reports coming from the occupied towns of Luq
and Bulo Hawo spoke about some casualties during the raid. At
least 12 people were killed of whom 8 were women in Jalabib
Islamic gowns during the first clashes in Bulo Hawo yesterday.
Loyalists of Al-Itihad also reported that the Ethiopians have
carried out abduction of men wearing beards and rape in Luq town.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, members from the executive committee of the Somali
National Front in Mogadishu have declined that any Ethiopian
troops were involved in the fighting in Gedo region yesterday.
The members including engineer Hassan Jama Hussein and Sheikh
Ibrahim Hosh Farah told the journalists that it was the SNF
forces who took over the two towns and their surrounding
villages. The members have called the remaining members of
Al-Itihad to surrender their weapons to the forces of SNF.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the militiamen of Al-Itihad Al-Islam
have been regrouping themselves 20 km east of Luq town. A number
of lorries transporting refugees who fled the fighting in the
region have also reached Mogadishu today. The refugees have
confirmed the presence of uniformed Ethiopian soldiers and their
tanks in Luq town and have also seen jet fighter planes on
surveillance around the town, but did not spoke about any
bombardment by the planes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
