<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Germany Fail to Reach Compromise over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- France and Germany today failed to
reach a compromise over the Stability Pact for the future European
single currency, three days away from the European Union (EU)
Amsterdam summit which is supposed to ratify the pact.
</P>
<P>
"A modification of the Stability Pact is excluded," said
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl at a press conference after the
summit held in Poitiers, southcentral France, the first since the
Socialist government of France came to power.
</P>
<P>
He said that discussions would continue "intensively" between
French and German officials this weekend, and that Bonn was
"sure" that the two sides would find a solution to the dispute
after the discussions.
</P>
<P>
France wishes to add clauses on job and economic growth into
the Stability Pact, which authorizes EU to impose heavy fines upon
any future European single currency country for excessive budget
spending.
</P>
<P>
"The Stability Pact is buckled. This is a fact," said Kohl.
</P>
<P>
President Jacques Chirac said that he would expect experts to
work out the details for solving the difference with Germany,
while French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said that the ideas
presented by France on adding a social volume into the pact should
be on the table of the Amsterdam summit.
</P>
<P>
Jospin denied that France wanted to force its ideas through the
pact and said that it is necessary to "respond to the demands of
the people who make up the European Union."
</P>
<P>
"The (French) government supports the single currency. It
supports that this single currency be realized on a foreseen
date," said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
But he added that "our economies cannot respond to the demands
of our people" only through monetary means.
</P>
<P>
"If one goes back to what are the foundations themselves of
the European Community which became then the European Union, the
dimensions of growth, the dimensions of employment, of fight
against unemployment, the need of concentration on the order of
economic policies, these are the demands," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
