<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Stonehenge Plan to Be Abandoned Due to Lack of Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Because of the lack of money, the
plan to improve the site of Britain's biggest tourist attraction,
the prehistoric monument of Stonehenge, will have to be abandoned,
a senior English Heritage official said today.
</P>
<P>
"We are extremely disappointed" at the decision of the
Millenium Commission not to finance the plan, chairman of English
Heritage, Sir Jocelyn Stevens, said at a news conference. The
English Heritage is responsible for the Stonehenge improvement
project.
</P>
<P>
Because of the decision of The Millenium Commission, one of the
bodies which distributes lottery funds, a 43 million pound (70
million US dollars) plan to expand the site of the mysterious
monument in southwest England and build a high-tech visitor center
will not be carried out.
</P>
<P>
Stonehenge is a circle of giant stones, dating from about 2,800
BC, which stand on their ends. Some still have huge stone lintels
lying across the top and an "altar stone" at the open northeast
side of the circle faces the rising sun.
</P>
<P>
Stevens said he believed part of the reason for the
commission's decision was its unhappiness with the private
financing of part of the project by Tussauds Group, part of the
Pearson media and leisure group.
</P>
<P>
"I was led to believe the Millenium Commission was discomfited
by the private finance element because it involved a profit," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Tussauds had agreed to invest 10 million pounds in the project
and to operate the visitor center which would explain the history
of Stonehenge and the many other prehistoric monuments around the
site. Tussauds had planned to make its profit from entrance fees
to the center, a spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Partner Countries Defense Ministers Meet at New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Defense ministers of the 16 NATO
states met on Friday in Brussels for the first time with their
counterparts from the alliance's 27 partner countries in the
framework of the newly established Euro-Atlantic Partnership
Council(EAPC).
</P>
<P>
The EAPC was formally launched two weeks ago in Sintra,
Portugal, at NATO's foreign ministers' meeting, with the aim of
promoting the political dialogue and military cooperation between
NATO states and their partner countries.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana briefed
the defense ministers from partner countries on the outcome of
NATO's defense ministers' meeting on Thursday, and the ministers
reviewed the development of the practical cooperation activities,
in the framework of Partnership for Peace(PfP) Program, taken
place in the past year.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time for the ministers (from NATO and
partner countries) to discuss in depth the military cooperation in
the enhanced Partnership for Peace(PfP) Program," a NATO
official said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that from now on partner countries would be
actively involved in both planning and implementation of the PfP
activities, and NATO-led peacekeeping missions "right from the
beginning".
</P>
<P>
The ministers praised at the meeting the accomplishments of the
NATO-led peacekeeping force, SFOR, in Bosnia and Herzegovina, to
which 15 partner nations contributed, and stressed the need fully
to implement the Bosnia peace accord.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion on the issue of NATO enlargement,
Slovenian defense minister Turnsek Tit and his Romanian
counterpart Victor Babiuc expressed their countries'
disappointment about Thursday's announcement by the United States
that it wanted only Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic to be
in NATO's first expansion, leaving outside Romania and Slovenia
which were strongly supported by a majority of NATO's European
alllies, including France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
"It is unlogical to exclude candidate countries which have
already met the accession criteria to joint in the first group,"
Mr Tit was quoted by a NATO official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We hope NATO's open door will open again," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The consensus on which countries will be admitted in the first
wave of the alliance's planned expansion into Eastern Europe is
expected to be reached at the end of this month, the same official
said.
</P>
<P>
Those countries will then receive the formal invitation, at
NATO's summit meeting in Madrid on July 8-9, to start accession
negotiations with NATO.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after the meeting, Mr Solana reaffirmed
that NATO's door would remain open after the first wave of
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
"Madrid will not be about winners and losers, all those who
wish to join NATO will have many opportunities to engage actively
with NATO to prepare for the moment when they are ready to join,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Prior to today's defense ministers' meeting, Secretary General
Solana has held a short separate meeting with the first deputy
defense minister of Russia, Mr Andrei Kokoshin.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, which is described by NATO officials as "a
good one", Mr Kokoshin is said to have told Mr Solana that Russian
President Boris Yeltsin was "enthusiastic" to see the early
implementation of "all the aspects" of the Russia-NATO Act signed
by the two sides last month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Industrial Production Growth Slows in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch industrial production
growth slowed to a year-on-year three percent in April compared
with the five percent increase seen in February and March, the
Dutch national statistics office CBS announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first four months together, industrial production
was up 3.9 percent in January-April 1997, compared with a
year-on-year rise of 1.7 percent recorded for the same period in
1996.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months, the wood and building materials
sector and the textile industry posted above-average increase of
11.7 percent and 8.4 percent respectively. The food, drinks and
tobacco sector, by contrast, saw just a 0.6 percent rise.
</P>
</TEXT>
