<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: U.S. Congress' Stand on Jerusalem Sparks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. congress' vote
recognizing Jerusalem as the "undivided and permanent" capital of
Israel sparked anger and condemnation of Lebanon's religious and
politician leaders today.
</P>
<P>
The non-binding resolution, which was adopted by the House of
Representatives of the United States Wednesday, also approved the
allocation of 100 million dollars to move the U.S. embassy from
Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Momammed Rashid Qabani, Mufti of the Republic of
Lebanon, described the U.S. house vote as an "obvious call for war
rather than peace and a deceit for the Arab."
</P>
<P>
It "indicates the degree of the American support for the
Israeli occupation in Palestine," said the Muslim Sunni spiritual
leader.
</P>
<P>
The resolution "exposes the Israeli and American intentions
against the Arab and encourages Israel to aggravate oppression
and terrorism against the Palestinian people inside the occupied
Palestine, and escalate threat against the Arab especially
Lebanon and Syria," Qabani said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mohammed Mahdi Shamsddin, spiritual leader of the
Muslim Shiite community in Lebanon, stressed that the vote made
Arabs, both Muslims and Christians, and non-Arabs "lose all their
confidence in the United States' role as a just and neutral broker
in the Arab-Israeli conflict."
</P>
<P>
"We say the Holy City (of Jerusalem) is Arab and the capital of
the Palestinian people, and the Holy City is Muslim and Christian
and is Jewish as well, but it is not Israeli," the Muslim Shiite
religious leader said.
</P>
<P>
Ali Khalil, chairman of the parliamentary committee for
foreign affairs, noted that the U.S. house resolution "destroies
the Middle East peace process and blows up what is left of hope in
a resumption of the Arab-Israeli peace negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Palestinians, who see Jerusalem as
the capital of their future state, and the Israelis have been
stalemated since three months ago when Israel began to construct a
Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. house's resolution "should be confronted by a real
Arab solidarity reaffirming our right of resisting the occupation
and working to eliminate it," Khalil said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the vote, Beirut's largest-circulated daily
An-Nahar accused the United States of "escalating the battle for
Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper's columnist described the resolution as
"shocking" because "for the first time in history it recognizes
Jerusalem as the undivided capital of Israel."
</P>
<P>
Pro-Syrian daily Ash-Sharq said that "Washington has sold, to
the Jews, a capital which does not belong to the Americans in the
first place."
</P>
<P>
It said that "once again, the United States has exceeded all
limits and unfairly appointed itself as a trustee over a region
which is thousands of miles away from America," adding "the
Americans have heightened tension in the region."
</P>
</TEXT>
