<HEADLINE> Somali Refugees Need Humanitarian Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- About 36,000 refugees who
fled from Somalia to south-eastern Ethiopia due to drought and
political strife are in dire need of relief food, an Ethiopian
official said today.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency quoted Abubeker Abdi, Head of the
Somali Region Disaster Prevention and Preparedness Bureau as
saying that the bureau had informed the Administration for
Refugee and Returnee Affairs and the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) that the refugees who settled
since last January in Dolo Odo and Filtu areas are exposed to
shelter and food shortage.
</P>
<P>
He said a team of representatives drawn from the
administration and the UNHCR had assessed the situation in the
areas and has been coordinating humanitarian organizations to
provide the refugees with emergency relief food.
</P>
<P>
The administration was contacting the Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) to facilitate the provision of food grain to
the areas, Abdi said.
</P>
<P>
A survey is being conducted with a view to carry out refugee
support program along side with emergency relief assistance,he
added. 
</P>
