<HEADLINE> Egypt, Libya Sign Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today returned home after winding up a two-day visit to Libya
during which the two countries signed a cooperation agreement on
trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, signed in Tobruk, Libya, the two
countries will exert their utmost efforts to enhance bilateral
trade.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also set up under the agreement joint
investment adventures in the domains of iron and steel industry,
petrochemicals, phosphates and cane sugar.
</P>
<P>
It was agreed that the two countries will form a permanent
ministerial committee which will meet every six months to ensure
the implementation of the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure from Libya, Mubarak held talks with Libyan
leader Muammar Gaddafi in Tobruk on bilateral relations and latest
regional and international developments.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also co-chaired today the final session of the
two-day Egyptian-Libyan joint higher committee meetings, which
issued a final communique stressing the two countries' keenness on
developing bilateral cooperation on various domains.
</P>
<P>
The final communique also reiterates the importance and
necessity of realizing Arab unity and maintaining the
European-Arab dialogue.
</P>
<P>
As for Turkey's cross-border military incursion to northern
Iraq to attack the out-lawed Kurdish Workers' Party, which has
fought a 13-year-old separatist war, the higher committee called
Turkey to withdraw immediately from Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
