<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California's Ties with Asia-Pacific Stressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 13 (Xinhua)--California, an American state
with the world's seventh largest economy, has been playing a
unique role in the country with an Atlantic-based economy shifting
to the Pacific-based, a seminar here was told.
</P>
<P>
Matt Fong, California's state treasurer, was speaking to a
group of business leaders and decision makers from the public and
private sectors attending a trade forum highlighting Hong Kong
beyond 1997.
</P>
<P>
Illustrating the shifting center of gravity, Fong said that 33
percent of the country's exported goods this year went to the
Pacific region as compared with 24 percent going to Europe, while
35 percent of the imported products coming from the Pacific as
against 19 percent from Europe.
</P>
<P>
In California, he said, one out of seven or eight jobs is
related to the Pacific trade and investment. Within five years,
the ratio will become one out of four, he added.
</P>
<P>
California boasts the largest Asian-Pacific population in the
United States. This highly diverse population possessing valuable
language, entrepreneurial and cultural skills, Fong said, is a
resource of ideas and deals and brings opportunities for the
state.
</P>
<P>
The treasurer said that California has more money in the form
of pension funds than any other state, which can be transferred
into investments in Asian countries with strong returns. With the
money we have we should position California as the Wall Street for
the Pacific," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking more directly on the theme of the forum, Fong said
that Hong Kong will remain an important place for Californians to
make investments with strong returns.
</P>
<P>
Other participants at the forum shared the view that Hong
Kong's return to China will ultimately be a leveling of the
Asia-Pacific trade playing field.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a recent trip to Shanghai, Fong said that the
dream of developing the metropolitan into a world-class financial
center could come true "within our lifetime."
</P>
<P>
Voicing his support for President Clinton's move to renew
China's MFN status, Fong said that Hong Kong buys three billion US
dollar products a year from California. Failure of MFN will
directly impair California's exporters, said the treasurer, adding
that as a result many working families will lose their jobs and
consumers will have to pay more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
