<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Latvia Can Join NATO Later </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States today told
the Baltic state of Latvia that it had a chance of joining the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) after the first wave of
expansion.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, U.S. President Bill Clinton said it wanted only
the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland to be NATO's first new
members.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is an integrated Europe. That goal embraces Latvia,"
said U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright before meeting
Latvian Foreign Minister Valdis Birkavs.
</P>
<P>
"NATO cannot advance promises of membership but we are
committed to a process that will help all aspiring nations
understand what they must do to make membership a possibility,"
Albright told reporters.
</P>
<P>
She added that the U.S. has made it clear that NATO will remain
open to all European countries that are able to contribute to its
goals.
</P>
<P>
Birkavs expressed his country's appreciation of the U.S.
announcement. "We fully support this major step in a process that
has to remain, and we are sure will remain, inclusive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Latvia "firmly" believes that NATO enlargement will not be
complete until the Baltic states are members of the alliance,
Birkavs added.
</P>
<P>
Insisting it would threaten its national security, Russia
strongly opposed the joining of the Baltic states in the alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
