<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Coupists Increasingly Isolated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Chang Yong)
</P>
<P>
LAGOS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The military coup leader who came
to power in Sierra Leone has become increasingly isolated both
internally and internationally, the Nigerian Television Authority
(NTA) reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
Denied by the United Nations, rejected by the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) and shunned by the
international community, the ruling junta was also opposed by the
local people.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want them (the military regime)," said a women in a
crowded street in the capital Freetown, shown by the NTA.
</P>
<P>
"The junta is threatening the country and causing bleeding,"
said Pious Foray, a local journalist being interviewed.
</P>
<P>
Parliament member Ibrahim Sorrie shared similar view, saying
he believed "at the end of some day, there will be a victory in
the country, not a victory for President Kabbah, not for the
ECOWAS, not for the military, but for the common sense of the
people."
</P>
<P>
In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Thursday
renewed his call for the Sierra Leonean military regime to step
down, saying the coup leaders cannot possibly cling to power in
the face of international isolation.
</P>
<P>
Annan hoped that the threat of force and the current efforts
to seek a negotiated resolution of the conflict would convince
them to return power to the country's legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
Junior Sierra Leonean army officers, allied with rebels of the
Revolutionary United Front (RUF), toppled the elected civilian
government led by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in a coup on May
25, forcing him to flee to neighboring Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The coup, the third in the country in five years, has
attracted an unprecedented international condemnation, and the
16-member sub-regional organization ECOWAS has vowed to reverse
it by force if the coupists failed to give up power.
</P>
<P>
Military clashes are still going on between the ECOWAS
peacekeeping force and the coupists while negotiations continued
for a peaceful resolution of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In Freetown, government and private sector employees defied
the military's repeated calls and continued their peaceful
strike, while schools, colleges, hospitals, banks and other
commercial houses remained closed.
</P>
<P>
This was "a vivid manifestation of opposition to the military
takeover", according to Sorrie, who is also secretary of a
four-member cross-party mediation team made up of
parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
The team also advocated for the formation of a broad-based
government of national unity including all political parties
represented in parliament, the RUF and other interest groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
