<HEADLINE> World Bank Okays 165 Mln Dlr Credit for India's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today announced
the approval of a 165 million U.S. dollar credit to the government
of India to help fight widespread malaria.
</P>
<P>
The project introduces a new approach to malaria control which
will help reduce deaths, disability and the heavy economic and
social toll associated with the disease.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 million people in high-risk districts, especially
those living tribal and rural areas, will directly benefit from
the project.
</P>
<P>
Malaria is a parasitic disease transmitted by certain
mosquitoes. There are more than 3 million cases in the southern
Asian country each year.
</P>
<P>
The project will help India create an enhanced and more
effective malaria control program that uses a better mix of
effective malaria control interventions, which are responsive to
local needs.
</P>
<P>
The project will begin phasing in seven states: Gujarat,
Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh and Rajasthan, Bihar and Orissa, and
Andhra Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
The total project cost is estimated at 204 million dollars. In
addition to the World Bank's credit, which will be channeled
through the bank's concessionary lending arm -- the International
Development Association, the Indian government will finance some
39 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
