<HEADLINE> Turkish President Calls for Democratic Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
said today that Turkey should resolve its present political crisis
within the framework of democracy.
</P>
<P>
Demirel made the remark at a press conference here amid
intensive and extensive criticism of the government's weakness in
checking the rapid expansion of Muslim fundamentalism in the
secular Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The president said that any political differences can be
debated in detail, but the democratic system and the state itself
must be respected.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller has
demanded Islamic Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan hand over his
post by June 18, or her True Path Party will withdraw from the
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The General Staff of the Turkish Armed Forces held a press
conference Wednesday and blasted Erbakan's tolerance for
fundamentalist force in the country.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the press conference is an ultimatum to the
Erbakan-led coalition government, Demirel said that what has been
done is "just a briefing."
</P>
<P>
In response to a question regarding the anti-fundamentalist
measures adopted by the National Security Council in February, the
Turkish president said these measures should be strictly carried
out, adding "If this (Erbakan's) government does not do it,
another government will do it."
</P>
<P>
Erbakan has agreed to transfer his premiership, but on
condition of a change of the election law.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, who leads the junior coalition partner True Path Party,
said on Thursday that the only solution to the current dilemma is
to hold an early election.
</P>
<P>
Although rumors about a possible military coup are described as
overstated, informed sources here said that Erbakan's coalition
government's collapse is imminent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
