<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, US Reach Agreement to Cut Red Tape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union and the United
States have reached a Mutual Recognition Agreement (MRA) which
will cut red tape, reduce costs and shorten delays in the
marketing of European products in America and vice-versa.
</P>
<P>
The MRA with the U.S. covers well over 40 billion U.S. dollars
worth of trans-Atlantic trade a year in some of the most important
sectors for the future -- telecommunications equipment, medical
devices and pharmaceuticals, as well as electromagnetic
compatibility and electrical safety.
</P>
<P>
Through the MRA, a product tested and approved in Europe to
U.S. quality and safety standards will automatically be ready for
sale in the U.S. without having to undergo a second round of U.S.
certification procedures.
</P>
<P>
The EU notes that the MRA will substantially cut the time it
takes to launch new products, ranging from mobile phones and
computers to drugs and tomographic X-ray systems.
</P>
<P>
"The MRA has been one of the crowning achievements of the new
trans-Atlantic relationship so far. It has assured that in real,
concrete ways the EU and the U.S. can work together to bring
benefits to business and consumers," said Sir Leon Brittan, EU
commissioner for external trade.
</P>
<P>
The MRA between the two sides is expected to be formally
initialed next week. A separate MRA has been reached with Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Provide 300 Mln Dlrs for Brazil's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today announced
the approval of a 300 million U.S. dollar loan for Brazil's
federal highway rehabilitation project.
</P>
<P>
The project will transfer responsibility of the national
highways to state governments to improve their maintenance,
increase private sector participation in their management, and
strengthen the technical capacity of the states' road departments
and the National Roads Department.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed to enhance human capital and
infrastructure development, the two bottlenecks in the country's
social and economic development. It also places emphasis on the
deregulation and privatization of infrastructure services,
efficient allocation of resources in the public sector, and
rebuilding and expansion of a deteriorated and inefficient highway
network in partnership with the private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
