<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Calls for British Envoy's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash today said he is not optimistic over Britain's mediation
in the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival here, Denktash expressed the hope
that British Envoy David Hannay will hold an equal attitude towards
the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
"Their duty is to listen to us and assist the U.N. Secretary
General (Kofi Annan), but not to give orders," he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan extended his invitations to Denktash and Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides Wednesday to hold direct meeting in New
York on July 9.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Turkish Foreign Ministry Under-secretary Onur
Oymen met with Hannay, who was shuttling among Cyprus, Greece and
Turkey on mediation mission, to discuss the upcoming Cyprus peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Oymen told the press that that Turkey and
Britain share common views regarding the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, Britain and Greece are the three guarantors of Cyprus'
independence under the 1960 treaty of establishment of the
republic.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Hannay said that there will not be a rapid
conclusion to the New York talks, adding that the breakdown of
barriers will certainly be a slow and long process.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the Island in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash had two U.N.-sponsored informal meetings
in Nicosia in October, 1994, which ended in a deadlock. The two
men have not met directly ever since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
