<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Won't Miss Single Currency Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 14 (xinhua) -- Italy will not miss entry into the
European single currency in 1999, Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said today.
</P>
<P>
"It would be a serious blow for everyone if we missed that
target by the established deadline," Dini said in Venice.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that it would be easier for European
Union countries to get their accounts in order for the single
currency if they were given one year more for preparations
</P>
<P>
"As I said some time ago, if we had had an extra year, it would
have been easier on everyone. The latest developments in Italy and
France show that this would have been helpful," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union set the date for establishing the single
currency at January 1, 1999, forcing its member states to carry
out structural adjustments, principally in budgets, which Dini
said had naturally caused sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
Dini said all European countries are willing to fight
unemployment. He was apparently responding to France's new
government's insistence that the stability pact, which was
intended to ensure compliance with the Maastricht parameters
following the start-up of the euro, should be accompanied by a
resolution on jobs and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The Italian job market, like that of France and Germany,
suffers from too many restrictions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must eliminate the barriers to entering certain key sectors
of the economy still dominated by corporations and corporativism,"
said minister.


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
