<HEADLINE> Italian Generals Moved Aside Over Somalia Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Two Italian generals, who were former
commanders of Italian troops on the peacekeeping mission in
Somalia, have been relieved of their current duties following
allegations that their troops tortured and killed civilian Somalis.
</P>
<P>
General Bruno Loi and General Carmine Fiore had asked to be
allowed to step down so as to "ease and speed up the investigation
underway", a statement from the office of the Army Chief of Staff
said.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that the Army Chief of Staff had "accepted the
request in order to contribute with the utmost determination to a
swift clarification of the affair".
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi announced Friday the
setting up of a joint civilian and military commission to launch a
full inquiry into the torture allegation raised by the news
magazine, Panorama.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the magazine first published reports about the
allegation of torture of Somalis by a former soldier.
</P>
<P>
Fresh reports, including photographs and interviews with two
more former soldiers, followed on Friday, adding two more
allegations of purported sexual violence against a Somali woman
and alleged killings of unarmed Somalis by the army.
</P>
<P>
General Loi, who headed the Italian forces in the United
States-led peacekeeping mission in Somalia from 1992 to 1993, said
today that he decided to put himself at the full disposal of the
Chief of Staff, "with the aim of easing and speeding up the work
of the commission".
</P>
<P>
Loi was replaced by General Fiore in Somalia, who led the
Italian troops there until their withdrawal in early 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
