<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Asks Turkey to Withdraw Troops From Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Istanbul (TURKEY), June 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister
Kamal El-Ganzouri said here today that Turkey must withdraw its
troops from northern Iraq as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan in
Istanbul, Ganzouri, who is to attend the D-8 Group summit to be
held Sunday, said that Turkey should end its cross-border military
incursion in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000-strong Turkish government troops launched a
massive military operation on May 14 in a bid to wipe out the
rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in the region.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Erbakan, said that Turkey sent troops to northern
Iraq in order to destroy the PKK camps there.
</P>
<P>
He said that the PKK rebels always infiltrate into Turkey
from northern Iraq to kill innocent Turks in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish prime minister reiterated that the Turkish
incursion followed a request for help by Iraq's Kurdistan
Democratic Party (KDP) leader Mesud Barzani.
</P>
<P>
Turkey respects Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity
both in history and now, stressed the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said: "Turkey will withdraw its troops from northern
Iraq when the target is achieved."
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported today that
Turkey has withdrawn some of the 50,000-strong troops, who are
still carrying out its campaign in the region.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian diplomatic sources, who declined to be named, told
Xinhua that Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak did not come to
Istanbul to attend the D-8 Group summit in a protest over
Turkey's military incursion in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has repeatedly criticized Turkey for launching a
massive military operation in pursuit of the PKK guerrillas in
northern Iraq, saying Turkey's action violated Iraq's independence
and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
President Mubarak has attempted to ask his Turkish
counterpart Suleyman Demirel to explain his country's military
operation in northern Iraq on his planned Cairo tour in April,
which was unexpectedly canceled at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
Realising Egypt's dissatisfaction with Turkey' latest military
operation against PKK, Turkish State Minister Abdullah Gul, as
the presidential envoy, flew earlier to Cairo to persuade the
Egyptian leader to attend the D-8 Group summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
