<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Businessmen Criticize Proposed Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Some leading chambers and trade
bodies in Bangladesh expressed their appreciation on the steps for
poverty alleviation in the proposed budget, but were critical
about the measures for the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, the Federation of Bangladesh
Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FBCCI) hailed some proposals,
such as housing fund for the elderly poor, old age pension and
Employment Bank, in the proposed national budget of the fiscal
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
However, the imposition of 2.5 percent surcharge on all imports
would adversely affect the pace of industrialization, said FBCCI
President Abdullah Harun in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the new tax proposal on cotton and textile machinery
should be reconsidered as it would seriously discourage the
entrepreneurs, said the President, who was also critical of the
proposals for enhancing the duty on the import of scrap ship.
</P>
<P>
In another statement, the Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce and
Industry (MCCI) said the industrial growth showed a massive
decline in 1996-97 fiscal year, but no remedial measures were
taken and this had not been addressed in the budget.
</P>
<P>
The chamber also expressed its disappointment over the absence
of new incentives to boost export.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest shortcoming of the budget, is that it has
significantly neglected the industrial sector in spite of the fact
that this sector registered the least growth, 3.6 percent,
compared to a double digit growth two years ago," said a statement
from the Dhaka Chamber of Commerce and Industry (DCCI).
</P>
<P>
The agro-based industries, which have large domestic and export
potentials, have also been neglected, said the statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
