<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diplomats Accused of Smuggling Ivory Into Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Diplomats have been accused of
smuggling ivory into Japan, the world's largest consumer of
elephant ivory, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The International Environmental Investigation Agency (EIA)
which is an active participant at the ongoing 10th conference of
the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species
(CITES) in Harare said 46 seizures of illegal ivory imports had
been made in Japan between 1989 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Records of the seizures revealed that most of the ivory
smuggled into Japan since the CITES trade ban was imposed in 1989
was already cut into small rectangular shapes for manufacture
into what the Japanese call "hanko".
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic smuggling of ivory was yet another serious problem,
charged the EIA.
</P>
<P>
"The easiest and safest way of illegal importations is the
ivory brought into Japan by diplomats. These people are promoting
illegal trade," said the agency, quoting a Japanese government
source.
</P>
<P>
Ivory seizures outside Japan, often destined for the Japanese
market, frequently consisted of "hanko" blanks, said the EIA,
adding that since the ban, seizures of hanko blanks indicated
that their manufacture had occurred in at least 12 African range
states which include countries of the Southern Africa Development
Community (SADC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
