<HEADLINE> Ouyahia Renamed as Algerian Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President Liamine Zeroual
reappointed today outgoing Prime Minister Ahmed Ouyahia as head of
of the new government of the country.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Ouyahia, who had been prime minister of the north African
nation since January, 1996, formally resigned Tuesday in order to
clear the way for the formation of a new government after last
week's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
Ouyahia's party, the National Democratic Rally, won 155 seats
in the elections, becoming the largest group in the 380-seat
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Ouyahia has been a close associate of President Liamine Zeroual
in implementing the policies of economic reforms and suppressing
terrorist groups in the past years.
</P>
<P>
Algeria's National Liberation Front (FLN), which won 64 seats
occupying the third place in the elections, has voiced its
objection to reappointment of Ahmed Ouyahia. The front has been
considered as a coalition partner in the new government.
</P>
<P>
Algeria has been plagued by Islamic insurgency since 1992 after
the authorities canceled the multiparty elections when an Islamic
party was poised to win. During the Five-year bloody insurgency,
more than 60,000 people were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
