<HEADLINE> WB to Fund Malaria Control in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has allocated 165
million US dollars from its soft loan affiliate, the International
Development Association, for malaria control in India, the Press
Trust of India (PTI) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The loan would usher in a new approach to malaria control in
the country which will help reduce deaths, disability and the
heavy economic and social toll associated with the disease, PTI
quoted a bank release as saying.
</P>
<P>
The release added that more than 200 million people in
high-risk districts in India, especially those living in tribal
and rural areas, will directly benefit from the project.
</P>
<P>
The project has five components: integrated early detection and
prompt treatment, a selective mosquito control component, a
medicated mosquito net program, intersectoral collaboration and
institutional strengthening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
