<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Iraqi-Syrian Ties Begin to Thaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, June 14 (Xinhua) -- A 34-member Iraqi trade
delegation started a week long visit yesterday to Syria headed by
chief of the Iraqi Chamber of Commerce Zohair Abdel-Ghafour Younis.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will hold talks with Syrian ministers of
finance, industry, economy and transport.
</P>
<P>
It will also meet with leading businessmen in an effort to
boost bilateral economic and trade cooperation and define
executive formulas for trade and industrial exchanges between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Crossing the Iraqi-Syrian borders yesterday, the Iraqi
delegation was warmly welcomed by Syrian businessmen led by chief
of the Syrian Chamber of Commerce Dr Rateb Al-Shallah.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the official Iraqi delegation is the first of its
kind since the disruption of diplomatic relations and closure of
borders between the two countries in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Sources of the Iraqi delegation expressed their strong desire
to visit Syrian and voiced the hope that the visit would yield
more cooperation accords and serve the interests of both countries
especially in the economic field.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will tour other Syrian provinces and industrial
cities, Syrian economic sources said.
</P>
<P>
It will sign agreements totalling some 15 million U.S. dollars,
on the Iraqi purchase of 10,000 tonnes of grain, 7,000 tonnes of
soap and detergents, and 6,000 tonnes of edible oil.
</P>
<P>
It will also conclude a deal on the purchase of Syrian
pharmaceuticals worth 1 million dollars and probe the possibility
of setting up joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the Iraqi delegation to Damascus is of great
significance as it turns a new page in Syrian-Iraqi economic and
trade cooperation that may eventually bring about normalization of
their relations, observers here believe.
</P>
<P>
It coincides with important developments in the Middle East
such as the emerging Turkish-Israeli military alliance, the
Turkish military operation in northern Iraq and the complete
standstill of the Arab-Israeli peace process.
</P>
<P>
The visit indicates the common aspiration of Baghdad and
Damascus to gradually normalize their relations as Syria advocates
Iraq's return to the Arab ranks and its participation in the
coming Arab summits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
