<HEADLINE> A Quarter of Dutch Graduates Jobless: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 14 (Xinhua) -- More than one in every four
recent graduates from universities in the Netherlands do not have
jobs, a report by Dutch job centers says.
</P>
<P>
The report said recent graduates of universities and secondary
schools are the most disadvantaged on the labor market. For school
leavers, this was because of government reorganizations and
limited demand for qualified school leavers in the commercial
sector.
</P>
<P>
However, those graduating from vocational secondary schools
have the greatest chance, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The weak position for recent college graduates is related to
their lack of experience, the study found.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment rates for recent college graduates rose two
percentage points to 29 percent last year, compared with a 17
percent rate for vocational school leavers.
</P>
<P>
Once university graduates landed their first jobs, their
situations greatly improved. This could be seen in the 5.6 percent
average unemployment rate for all university graduates, which was
well below the national average of 7.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
