<HEADLINE> Nakamura Clocks World 100m Backstroke Best This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Mai Nakamura clocked the world best
time this season to win the women's 100-meter backstroke in the
Japanese national swimming championships here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The school girl from Niigata clocked one minute 01.18 seconds
to better her own previous national mark of 1:01.42 set at the
East Asian Games in Pusan last month.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old scored the world's best time of the season to
win the 200m in 2:11.05 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"But the current world record is less than 1:01. My real goal
is to break it," she said.
</P>
<P>
Nakamura's time was one hundredth of a second faster than
American Beth Botsford's gold winning time at the Atlanta Olympic
Games, while China's He Cihong holds the current world record of
1:00.16 set in Rome in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100m breaststroke final, Chikara Nakashita, who
scored the world best time of the season to win the 200m in
2:13.44, failed to shine again losing to Yoshinobu
Miyazaki. Miyazaki timed 1:02.79 to beat Nakashita by 0.25 seconds.
 
</P>
