<HEADLINE> Senior Legislator Stresses Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior legislator said here
today that China has made big progress in the protection of its
environment and resources, but formidable challenges and hard work
lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
Wang Bingqian, vice-chairman of Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), was speaking at a forum on
environmental and resource protection, which was held to sum up
the work on legislation and law enforcement related to the
environment and resources.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the forum will help to lay a solid legal
foundation for the country's sustainable economic growth strategy.
</P>
<P>
Since its formation in March, 1993, the Eighth NPC has stepped
up legislation on the issues, working out six laws on
environmental protection and nine laws on resources. In addition,
the State Council and local governments have enacted a large
number of rules and regulations in this regard, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the state has taken various measures to
strengthen law-enforcement, and related environmental protection
activities have had a great impact on the entire society.
</P>
<P>
However, the legislator pointed out that for a long time,
China's rapid development and backward management have put great
pressure on the country's resources and environment.
</P>
<P>
The trend of a deteriorating natural ecology continues,
environmental pollution is worsening and the conditions of
resources inspire no optimism, therefore it is urgent to stick to
the sustainable development strategy, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
