<HEADLINE> Palestinian Leadership Slams U.S. Congress Resolution on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian leadership has
condemned U.S. Congress for its resolution recognizing Jerusalem
as the undivided capital of Israel, according to a report of
JMCC, a Palestinian press service based in East Jerusalem,
today.
</P>
<P>
A statement, which was released at the end of the weekly
session of the Palestinian leadership in Nablus, West Bank,
Friday night, noted that the resolution harms U.S. credibility
and contravenes the letter guarantee given to the Palestinians
on the eve of the 1991 Madrid Middle East peace conference.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives Tuesday also voted to
provide 100 million dollars for moving the U.S. Embassy in
Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem. The resolution has met with
stern condemnation from the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat chaired the meeting which
was attended by Palestinian National Authority (PNA) cabinet
members, PLO Executive Committee members and speaker of
Palestinian Council. The participants also discussed the latest
political developments in light of the Egyptian mediation by
Presidential advisor Osama el-Baz between the Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the Palestinian leadership blamed
Israel for the recent tension in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Hundreds of Palestinian protesters clashed with
Israeli troops in Rafah, southern Gaza Strip. The soldiers
opened fire killing one Palestinian and wounding more than 20.
</P>
<P>
The statement refuted the accusations leveled by the Israeli
authorities that the PNA was behind the demonstration, noting
that it was because of the provocative construction of a fence
around the Jewish settlement of Morag and of the installation of
a memorial for an Israeli soldier killed by Palestinian fire
last September. 
</P>
