items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- A Federal jury yesterday voted unanimously that Timothy J.
McVeigh. a 29-year-old former soldier, should be sentenced to
death for the bombing of the Federal Building in Oklahoma City on
April 19, 1995, which took 168 lives and injured 850 other people.
</P>
<P>
-- The House ways and Means Committee approved a Republican
tax-cutting bill over unanimous Democratics opposition early
yesterday, setting Congress on a collision course with the Clinton
Administration over how to divide the tax reduction agreed on in
their balanced-budget plan.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- On the eve of what he has promised will be a major statement
on America's racial division, U.S. President Bill Clinton said
yesterday that his goal is to prepare the nation for a time within
a few decades when the country is so diverse that whites will no
longer constitute a clear majority.
</P>
<P>
-- Four committees in Congress have voted to overturn major
Clinton administration rulings interpreting the new welfare law,
signaling widespread Republican support to allow states to
privatize welfare programs and pay recipients less than the
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
Washington Times:
</P>
<P>
