<HEADLINE> HK Provisional Legislature Adopts Four Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) passed the third readings of four bills at its 11th
plenary meeting here this afternoon after it resumed
second-reading debates on them.
</P>
<P>
The four bills are the National Flag and National Emblem Bill,
the Regional Flag and Regional Emblem Bill, the Societies
(Amendment) Bill 1997 and the Public Order (Amendment) Bill 1997.
</P>
<P>
Before the three-hour debates, Michael Suen, secretary for
policy coordination of the Chief Executive Office of the HKSAR,
said that the PLC's bill committees of the four bills had made
detailed study at the previous meetings.
</P>
<P>
He said that after the consultations between the bill
committees and the representatives of the Chief Executive of the
HKSAR, some literary and technical adaptations had been made to
the bills.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the adaptations would make the clauses
 of the bills clearer and more accurate in expression.
</P>
<P>
On the National Flag and National Emblem Bill, he said that the
 draft of the bill aimed at implementing the Law on the National
Flag and the Law on the National Emblem of the People's Republic
of China adopted by the Standing Committee of China's National
People's Congress in 1990 and 1991 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Thus, he said, the contents of the bill should be in line with
the two national laws.
</P>
<P>
The Regional Flag and Regional Emblem Bill aims at providing
use, manufacture and protection of the regional flag and emblem of
 the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Suen said that the Chief Executive Office had taken into
account various suggestions on the amendment to the bill.
</P>
<P>
On the Societies (Amendment) Bill 1997 and the Public Order
(Amendment) 1997, he said that the drafts of the bills were the
fruit of soliciting opinions from HK citizens and they also met
the HKSAR government's goal of seeking a balance between ensuring
citizens' freedom and maintaining social order.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
