<HEADLINE> Foundations Help Develop Social Welfare in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Like 133 other needy old people in
Luwan District in Shanghai, 94-year-old Xu Aying receives 150 yuan
every month from the Old-Age Foundation of the district.
</P>
<P>
The foundation is one of the 67 such assistance funds in
Shanghai which distribute money for social welfare, education
fees, old-age pensions, culture and the arts, children's aid
programs, medical research, and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The Soong Ching Ling Foundation was the first of its kind that
was formed in the city.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, it donated 100,000-yuan worth (12,000 US dollars) of
food to the Shanghai Children's Welfare Institute, and also gave
about 200,000 yuan (24,000 US dollars) to Lijiang District in
southwest China's Yunnan Province, which had been severely damaged
by earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Automobile Development Education Foundation has spent
3.66 million yuan (850,000 US dollars) to improve education and
trained a large group of professional personnel for the automobile
industry.
</P>
<P>
Some 25,000 poverty-stricken families have benefited from 110
million yuan (13 million US dollars) of funding provided by the
Shanghai Charity Foundation since it was established in 1994.
</P>
<P>
This organization also offered training programs to more than
7,000 handicapped people and laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
The city's foundations have gained a good reputation for their
strict management, supervision and use of funds. The Shanghai
Charity Foundation publicizes the income, expenditure and use of
its funds each year through the media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
