<HEADLINE> Health of French Youths Described as "Alarming" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The health of French youths and
children aged from 10 to 24 is described as "alarming" by the
official French High Committee of Public Health, two French
medical dailies reported today.
</P>
<P>
The daily "Impact" quoted the committee report as saying that
72 percent of the youths aged from 10 to 24 suffer from at least
one disease or a health affliction, while 43 percent of them have
an average of one health problem in a year.
</P>
<P>
About 802 youngsters aged from 15 to 24 committed suicide in
1995 in the country, said the report.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of the deaths among the French youths are
caused by accidents, about 3,000 of them losing their lives in
traffic accidents in 1993, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Suicide accounted for 15 percent of the deaths among French
youths and disease, 12 percent. The suicides tripled among boys
aged 15 to 24 from 1960 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
The daily "Medecin" quoted the committee report as saying the
death rate caused by accidents and suicides in France is the
highest among European Union countries, and double that of Britain.
</P>
<P>
Seven percent of French school children aged 11 to 19 said
that they were depressed, and 75 percent of high school students
complained about depression and anxiety because of heavy school
work, said the report.
</P>
<P>
About 15.4 percent of the depressed high school students were
reported to have tried to commit suicide at least once.
</P>
<P>
The reports said one in seven French youths had used drugs, and
1.1 percent of college students and 2.5 percent professional
school students had used cocaine or heroin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
