<HEADLINE> Iran's Pro-Rafsanjani Politicians to Form Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- A group of high-ranking
politicians who support the liberal policies of Iranian
President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani will form a political party
in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Today's Persian-language daily Akhbar reported that the group
known as Servants of Reconstruction (G-6) will form their party
by the middle of August.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the formation of the political party
has been high on the agenda of the 64-year-old outgoing moderate
president, who has to step down on August 3 because the
Constitution bars him from running the third consecutive term of
office.
</P>
<P>
They noted that Rafsanjani will certainly remain on the
political arena and will exercise his strong influence as
chairman of the State Expediency Council and a leader of the
political party.
</P>
<P>
Akhbar reported that the liberal group, Servants of
Reconstruction of Iran, has prepared drafts of the bylaws of the
party, which will be presented to the Iranian Judiciary for
approval.
</P>
<P>
Formed on December 31, 1995 in the run-up to the Fifth
Parliamentary Elections, the G-6 group resumed its intense
political activities this year by backing president-elect
Seyyed Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a source whose spoke on condition of anonymity, Akhbar
said that the party will be named after the group's name,
"Servants of Reconstruction of Iran."
</P>
<P>
The same source said that the group has recruited such notable
figures as Abdullah Nouri, leader of one of a powerful coalition
of the leftists and liberal MP's in the Iranian parliament, and
Faezeh Hashemi, a feminist MP and daughter of Rafsanjani.
</P>
</TEXT>
