<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Leaves for Istanbul for D-8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa left here today for Istanbul, Turkey, leading the Egyptian
delegation to the foreign ministerial meeting to prepare for the
Islamic summit Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The eight populous Muslim countries, namely Egypt, Turkey,
Pakistan, Iran, Nigeria, Bangladesh, Malaysia and Indonesia, are
expected to sign a declaration launching the Developing-8 (D-8)
economic group at Sunday's summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal al-Ganzouri will attend the
summit on behalf of President Hosni Mubarak, who has apologized
for not attending.
</P>
<P>
Senior foreign ministry officials of the eight Islamic member
states wound up their meeting in Istanbul Friday in agreement
with presenting a few draft resolutions, which were to be
endorsed at the D-8 summit.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian chief delegate, Deputy Foreign Minister Sayed Kassem
al Masri said that Egypt has presented a bill on setting up a
corporation for marketing and trade to be endorsed at the summit
with a view to promoting trade cooperation among the group
members.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision made by the foreign ministers of the
group during their first meeting in Istanbul, each member state
will be responsible for a certain field of cooperation. Egypt was
put in charge of the trade and cotton industry sectors.
</P>
<P>
Moussa will hold talks with foreign ministers of other
participating countries on means of enhancing bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He will also discuss with senior Turkish officials, including
Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller, the recent developments in the
region, with an emphasis on the Turkish incursion into northern
Iraq. 
</P>
