<HEADLINE> Kenya Issues New Bill Before Planned Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has issued
the much-awaited Peaceful Assemblies Bill just before the
opposition rallies set for June 21 in nine major towns in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Under the new bill, political rallies and other public
gatherings will no longer need to require a government permit,
but a 14-day notification to district officers to facilitate for
security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
If the district officers rejects an application for any rally,
they must notify the applicant in writing within five days before
the scheduled function.
</P>
<P>
The officers also have the right to cancel any permit so
issued or make amendments to the permits.
</P>
<P>
All other meetings of public bodies, trade unions or
professional organizations have been excluded from this
requirement.
</P>
<P>
The bill is to be tabled in the parliament next week to seek
the lawmakers' approvement to have the current Public Order Act
replaced.
</P>
<P>
Under the existing bill, any administrative officer or police
officer could stop or prevent the holding of a licence issued.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition parties tried to hold two rallies with no
permit from the government last month.
</P>
<P>
The rallies thus were broken up by Kenyan anti-riot police
amid turmoils which injured dozens of people and caused
businesses to a complete standstill in downtown Nairobi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
