<HEADLINE> Guangdong to Set up Anti-Cancer Foundation for Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 14 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
will set up a special foundation to help pay for expensive medical
costs of children who have cancer.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the death rate of children under five
years old who have cancer in Guangdong is higher than the
country's average rate.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said that both the cure and survival rates of these
young cancer patients can reach 70 percent -- much higher than
that of the adults.
</P>
<P>
However, about two percent of China's cancer-stricken children
don't receive treatment because their families can't afford
it. For example, the treatment for acute leukemia usually costs
200,000 (24,000 US dollars) to 300,000 yuan (36,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The foundation, which was initiated by seven big hospitals in
the province with approval from the provincial Health Department,
will provide financial aid to the young patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
