<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Unveils Budget Aimed at Boosting Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistan government today
unveiled a budget for the 1997-98 fiscal year which is aimed at
controlling inflation and creating jobs.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a post-budget press conference here today, Finance
Minister Sartaj Aziz said that these objectives would be realized
by putting economy back on rails, reviving the industrial sector
and boosting exports.
</P>
<P>
Clear-cut policy measures have been taken to seek viable and
long term solution of the severe economic issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that excise duty was reduced on different items
including telephone, cigarette, beverages, bus bodies, television,
text books which would not only help revive the industry but would
also benefit the consumers.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the sales tax has been slashed on medicines, poultry
and there was no fresh sales tax on the food items, ensuring
relief to the common man, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the services provided by professionals including
doctors, lawyers, accountants and architects have also been
exempted from excise duty which would also take care of the
consumer class.
</P>
<P>
Dispelling the impression about the budget as mere industry
friendly, the finance minister said the budgetary measures aim at
cutting down inflation and create job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"The social sector is the second wheel of our economic agenda"
he said, adding allocation of 100 billion rupees (about 2.5
billion U.S. dollars) has been provided for the uplift and the
social conditions of the masses including health and education.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the poverty alleviation program, he said, it is a
medium term program with far-reaching impact towards overcoming
this menace.
</P>
<P>
The government also significantly reduced the non-development
expenditures and will have tight control over it even in the next
fiscal year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said that the measures taken in the budget
for 1997-98 would be implemented in true spirit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
