<HEADLINE> Ramos Says He Looks Forward to New Role After '98 polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
hinted today that his role after his term expires on June 30, 1998
would be to give advice and direction as a senior statesman.
</P>
<P>
"I will provide advice and direction as a senior statesman, not
in government," Ramos said in Asingan, Pangasinan Province, where
he and his wife registered as voters for next year's local and
general elections.
</P>
<P>
About 40 million Filipinos are expected to register as voters
in the four-day general registration which started today. The
general listing will continue tomorrow and on June 21-22.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine constitution, the president serves a
single six-year term. Ramos has repeatedly promised to step down
next year, but he is still pushing for charter changes.
</P>
<P>
"I have made it very clear that for me, our 1987 Constitution
must be open to amendments on the basis of the right of our people
who might have the initiative to petition for constitutional
amendments," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos said that he has nothing to do with the move by some
sectors to extend his term.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties have accused Ramos of trying to lift his
term limits by amending the constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
