<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan has stated that his country might go to an American
court to seek a refund of 628 million US dollars it paid for the
purchase of F-16 aircraft, according to the official Associated
Press of Pakistan (APP) today.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan told APP two days ago that this might be the best
choice for the Pakistani government because it has fallen through
to get the refund through aircraft sale to a third country.
</P>
<P>
The position of the United States is that it cannot deliver the
aircraft due to the Pressler legislation, nor can it refund the
money before it goes to the Congress Appropriation Committee, Ayub
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it was reported that Indonesia, who was to buy the
F-16 aircraft, had disbanded the deal unilaterally in protest
against the U.S. congress' criticism of its human rights
situation.
</P>
<P>
Ayub said that the Pakistani government would take a decision
within next few months if it would go to a court or not.
</P>
<P>
"We can not only claim the principal amount but also the
interest and damages from the special fund," he added.  
</P>
