<HEADLINE> Dhaka Stock Price Index Rises amidst Declining Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE) All
Share Price Index increased 16 points amidst declining trade both
in volume and value last trading week ending on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark index of Bangladesh's largest bourse rose to
1,157.43 from the previous week's closing balance of 1,141.34,
while market capitalization also increased to 96.8 billion taka
(about 2.25 billion dollars) from 95.46 billion taka (about 2.22
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
During the week, however, only 1.57 million shares and
debentures valued 320.09 million taka (about 7.44 million U.S.
dollars) were traded against 1.66 million shares and debentures
worth 352.77 million (about 8.2 million dollars) of the previous
week.
</P>
<P>
Market observers attributed this decline in value and volume to
the cautious attitude of the investors for the announcement of the
budget for the 1997-98 fiscal year on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior market analyst, certain fiscal proposals
announced in the budget for the coming fiscal year would revamp
and rejuvenate the share market.
</P>
<P>
Shares of 18 state-owned enterprises were planned to be off
loaded through stock exchange, which would augment the supply of
shares on the primary market, said the analyst.
</P>
<P>
Abolition of quota system in Initial Public Offerings would
attract more retail investors in the shares while increase in
quota of non-resident Bangladeshis is also a very wise move, the
analyst said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
