<HEADLINE> Turkish PM: D-8 Group Not Competes With World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, TURKEY, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan said here today that the eight Muslim countries
bloc, known as D-8 Group, aims to expand cooperation among its
member countries instead of competing with any international
groups.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting of ministerial council of the
D-8 Group in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey, Erbkan said
that the D-8 Group consisting of eight member states with a
population of 800 million is a strong power in the world,
aiming to improve their people's living standards.
</P>
<P>
He said that the D-8 Group means "peace instead of
conflict, dialogue instead of confrontation, cooperation instead of
exploitation, justice instead of double standards, equality
instead of discrimination, democracy instead of oppression."
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, who is an enthusiastic sponsor of the Muslim
countries organization, stressed that the D-8 bloc spares
no efforts to embrace all the countries throughout the world
and to boost global cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On her part, Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller said
that the D-8 Group is a new belief to promote peace and
stability in the world.
</P>
<P>
She expressed the hope that the Istanbul meeting will shed
new lights in dialogue and cooperation in this newly formed
world.
</P>
<P>
Ciller said: "We see in the near future a big project
will take place in this D-8 Group."
</P>
<P>
Pakistani diplomat N. Ahmet Asrar told Xinhua that Pakistan
strongly supports the D-8 Group, which was initiated by the
Turkish prime minister, saying that the D-8 Group is aimed at
cooperating economic and trade fields among the Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting, which was held at the Ciragan Hotel,
was making preparations for the D-8 Group Summit Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Summit will officially announce the establishment of
the eight Muslim developing countries bloc, which was formed on
October 11, 1996 on the auspices of Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Group consists of Turkey, Iran, Nigeria, Egypt,
Pakistan, Bangledesh, Malaysia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim countries group's combined GNPs total 600 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the D-8 Group has provoked dissatisfaction
from the United States and other Western countries. They believe
that the Muslim bloc is directed against the G-7 Group of
the Western world.
</P>
<P>
Some Central Asian countries, which are also Muslim-dominated
countries, are also dissatisfied with the D-8 Group because
they are not invited to the bloc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls Take NBA Title for Fifth Time in Seven Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHICAGO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chicago Bulls won their fifth
NBA title in seven years Friday after beating the Utah Jazz 90-86
at home.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jordan led the Bulls with 39 points and 11 rebounds and
was named the Finals Most Valuable Player for the fifth time.
</P>
<P>
Steve Kerr's shot with five seconds to go put the Bulls up for
the last time in a game Utah had led from late in the first
quarter until just under nine minutes left in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
On Utah's final possession, Chicago's Toni Kukoc tipped an
inbounds pass from Bryon Russell. Scottie Pippen completed the
steal and tossed it back toward Kukoc, whose layup loosed the now
familiar celebration in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
Jordan said Pippen, who has played alongside Jordan on all of Chicago's
championship campaigns, deserved a share of the MVP honor.
</P>
<P>
"He's like a little brother to me," Jordan said of
Pippen. "That's what brothers do, we share our successes."
</P>
<P>
Pippen added 23 points and nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of people watch scorers, and Michael is one of the best
scorers in this game. But Scottie's defense was a one-man wrecking
crew," Bulls coach Phil Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
Malone led Utah with 21 points and Jeff Hornacek had 18 for the
Jazz.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls had trailed from early in the first quarter when
Kerr, who has struggled with his shooting off the bench
throughout the series, sank a three-pointer with just under nine
minutes left to play, putting Chicago ahead 74-73.
</P>
<P>
The three-pointer capped a 10-0 run that erased a nine-point
deficit after the first minute of the final period. Kerr scored
five of those points and Pippen scored the other five, while
Jordan was on the bench.
</P>
<P>
Jordan returned with eight and a half minutes to go and
contributed 10 more points, making it 86-83 with a 16-foot jumper
with 2:02 to play.
</P>
<P>
Utah's Russell tied it again at 86-86 with a three-pointer with
1:44 to go.
</P>
<P>
After missed chances on either side, Chicago took the ball on
an inbounds pass.
</P>
<P>
As usual, the Bulls gave the ball to Jordan, who drew the
double team, faked a shot and passed to Kerr, who was wide open at
the top of the key and sank the deiciding basket.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls have now won all five of their appearances in the NBA
finals, starting with their victory over the Los Angeles Lakers in
1991.
</P>
<P>
That was the first of their "Three-peat" run. They went on to
beat Portland in 1992 -- when they also rallied in the fourth
quarter of the final game -- and Phoenix in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Jordan missed all of the 1993-1994 season and most of the
1994-1995 campaign while retired. But he returned to form last
year when Chicago defeated Seattle to claim their fourth title.
</P>
<P>
Chicago's five titles in seven years surpasses the five in nine
years won by the Los Angeles Lakers in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Utah, who had never before reached the finals, lost the first
two games in Chicago then fought back to equalize with victories
in games three and four in Salt Lake City. They lost game five at
home, and returned to Chicago facing the formidable task of
winning two games on the Bulls' home court.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0116 </DOCNO>
