<HEADLINE> Kenya to Import More Maize for Food Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government targets to
import 18,000 tons of maize before July for the ongoing famine
relief operation countrywide, with some 76,000 tons of maize
having been imported since February.
</P>
<P>
The maize importation is aimed at bridging a sharp drop in the
commodity's supplies after a recent severe drought that hit the
most parts of the eastern African country, the "East Africa
Standard" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The imported maize are mainly from South Africa and the United
States, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Between February and June, the country also imported a total
of 232,284 tons of wheat.
</P>
<P>
Relief supplies are to be completed by July when the country
expects to register improved maize harvest, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, the current unexpectedly dry weather in some areas in
northern Kenya is likely to have adverse effects on maize and
wheat yield there, experts warned. 
</P>
