<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Tipped on Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenya should make poverty
alleviation a priority from now as nearly half of its population
live in absolute poverty, a U.N. official was quoted by today's
"Daily Nation" newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Both life expectancy and primary school enrollment rates have
declined in the eastern African country over recent years, said
Nancy Asanga, the U.N. Development Program country
representative.
</P>
<P>
She called for a re-evaluation of Kenya's past development
plans on poverty alleviation to make them more concrete and
effective.
</P>
<P>
"Comparatively, Kenya ranks lower than the average of all
developing countries. The impending questions to all of us are
whether this is the rightful ranking for a country like it, why
and what needs to be done," she said.
</P>
<P>
Except for 1994, Kenya's ranking, according to the Human
Development Indices, dropped from 113rd position in 1991 to 134th
this year. Last year it held the 128th position.
</P>
<P>
Kenyans' life expectancy fell from 59.7 in 1991 to 53.6 this
year while primary school enrollment rate dropped two percent to
55 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
