<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Operation Rate of South Korea's Car Industry to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The operation rate of South Korea's
domestic auto industry is expected to keep falling throughout the
next four years, the Korea Automobile Manufacturers Association
and Kia Motors Corporation said today.
</P>
<P>
The country's car output rate is expected to fall from 80.1
percent last year to 72.9 percent this year and 53.9 percent by
the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the combined production capacity of South Korean car
manufacturers, owing to their persistent buildup, would continue
to grow from 3.5 million units last year to 6.4 million in
2001. The growth will lead to an overstock of 3.45 million units,
about five times more than the 690,000 cars in 1996, said industry
sources.
</P>
<P>
Even at the 72.9 percent operation rate, the combined output
capacity this year, seen to reach 4 million units, will cause an
oversupply of more than 1 million units for the first time, with
fierce competition among automakers further straining their
profitability, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They said the increasing supply excess in South Korea's auto
industry was due to slowing demand for new car models in
industrial countries, various governmental regulations on
preventing traffic congestion, environmental pollution and large
carmakers' ambitious capacity buildup to attain global-scale
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
The Economist, a Britain-based financial weekly, has recently
estimated the global auto industry's factory operation rate at
72.9 percent in 1996 with total production capacity of 68 million
units, resulting in more than 18 million cars in oversupply.
</P>
<P>
The magazine forecast that the capacity use ratio would drop to
below 55 percent by 2001, with excess supply surpassing 20 million
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
It said that the situation would lead to fierce sales
competition among international carmakers. It expected a
global-scale restructuring of the industry through merger and
acquisition, strategic alliances and readjustment of manufacturing
lines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspended Hurdler Flenoy Competes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Suspended 400-meter hurdler
Stephon Flenoy Friday came out to run in the U.S. athletics
championships in Indianapolis. However, he finished last in his
preliminary race.
</P>
<P>
Flenoy's complicated situation came to a head Friday when the
IAAF waived its "contamination" rule, which could have led to the
suspension of all runners who competed against him.
</P>
<P>
Even with the IAAF backing away from its hardline stance, the
race went off only after the competitors, including world
record-holder Kevin Young, signed a waiver form from U.S. track
officials conceding that they knew about the contamination risk.
</P>
<P>
Flenoy had been suspended by the USA Track and Field (USATF)
April 4 after a drug test revealed a ratio of testosterone to
epitestosterone higher than the acceptable 6-to-1.
</P>
<P>
He took the case to arbitration and an aribtrator ruled that he
had not received a fair hearing before a USATF board and ordered
him reinstated into the U.S. championships.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF decision came after a letter from USATF president Pat
Rico to IAAF president Primo Nebiolo requested the waiver on
behalf of 400-meter hurdlers in the championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
