<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rosy Dream of Small Village Comes True (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Dounan, in Chenggong county in
southwest China's Yunnan province, is a small village that can not
be found on a map, but it is now widely known as the home of
representative offices of several dozen companies engaged in the
beautiful business of flowers.
</P>
<P>
Within a dozen years, Dounan has developed from an obscure
small village into the largest flower trading center in southwest
China and the sole village-level flower market in the whole
country.
</P>
<P>
Everyday, large amounts of flowers are shipped to the village
from the fields nearby, and are then wholesaled to every corner of
the country and even to foreign countries. Now, more than four
million flowers are transacted in the village daily, worth over
300,000 yuan. Entering the market full of various kinds of red,
white and yellow flowers, one cannot help but feel like walking in
a very big flower garden.
</P>
<P>
In the fields outside the village some 180 ha of flower land
are covered with white plastic shelters, where the flowers bloom
all the year round.
</P>
<P>
Li Tingren, director of the Village Committee in his fifties,
said: "I am sure that most people in the flower business in China
know Dounan."
</P>
<P>
Dounan people began to grow flowers in the late 1980s, when the
business just started to grow in China.
</P>
<P>
Due to fine weather conditions, the village's flower
cultivation grew rapidly in line with high social demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two WNBF Spies Face Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Two men accused of spying for the
West Nile Bank Front (WNBF) face the charge of treason, "The New
Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mathia Oriyo, a driver in Arua District in the north-west, and
Moses Abdallah, a photographer of the same district, yesterday
have been committed to the high court for the trial, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Betty Khisa, resident state attorney, told the court that the
two accused took part in activities aimed at overthrowing the
government of Uganda in various occasions in Arua and Morobo,
southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The accused collected and delivered information to the WNBF
about the deployment of the government troops and the movement of
Colonel James Kazini, commander of the Fourth Division, the
attorney said.
</P>
<P>
Documents captured from Oriyo indicated he also monitored
activities of Sudan People's Liberation Army, a rebel group
acting in southern Sudan, and gave financial and material support
for WNBF rebels, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 alleged WNBF rebels are still in custody waiting
for charge, the report said.
</P>
<P>
WNBF is a crippled rebel group which was acting in the
north-west and had bases in southern Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rosy Dream of Small Village Comes True (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By 1995 most of the village's arable land had been switched for
growing flowers. Villagers stopped growing all other crops and
changed their life habbit with more money in hand.
</P>
<P>
The flower market gradually took shape. In the beginning, some
villagers took flowers to community centers themselves for
sale. Later, a primary wholesale market developed on an open space
outside the village as the demand for flowers were increasing.
</P>
<P>
Neighboring villages followed suit quickly. They also shipped
flowers to the wholesale market in the village. More and more
wholesalers appeared.
</P>
<P>
Officials of Dounan village decided to expand the market. They
spent over three million yuan building flower wholesale
facilities, including some 1,000 trading stalls.
</P>
<P>
Every dawn sees both flower farmers and dealers throng to the
market.
</P>
<P>
The whole village has been becoming increasingly rich and
prosperous from the returns of flowers, Li Tingren revealed.
</P>
<P>
Historically Dounan villagers lived just on growing
grain. Until the end of the 1970s some ten percent of the
villagers still did not have enough to eat and wear, and the per
capita net income was 41 yuan. Most people lived in thatched
houses.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, villagers began to grow vegetables besides
grain, and sold vegetables to city dwellers. More and more
thatched houses were replaced by brick ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rosy Dream of Small Village Comes True (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"However, the village realized prosperity it dreamed only when
it was connected with flowers," said Li.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, the per capita net income reached 3,702 yuan. More
than 1,500 families moved into concrete cement buildings, and over
300 families were equipped with telephones.
</P>
<P>
What is more important is that the flower business has
broadened people's vision, Li said. Many villagers turned into
flower traders. Asked what flowers sell well at what season, an
illiterate old man who was helping with packaging answered without
hesitation that roses sell best on Valentine's Day and carnations
on the Mother's Day. The same answer could be made even by small
school boys.
</P>
<P>
However, Li Tingren said that the flower business of Dounan has
just taken off in view of high demand, adding that the families
grow flowers still separately on small scales and the prices
sometimes go up and down by large margins.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the village is considering building a flower
market several times as large as the present one and setting up a
flower company that integrates production with sales.
</P>
<P>
"By that time we will be able to make real big money," he said.
</P>
<P>
The flower industry is now encouraged by government, he said,
and Yunnan plans to build itself into a kingdom of flowers and the
provincial capital of Kunming plans to build itself into China's
capital of flowers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0133 </DOCNO>
