<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 06:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Welcomes UN Resolution Asking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon welcomed today a
resolution of the United Nations' general assembly blaming
Israel for the shelling of a U.N. peacekeeping force camp at
Qana in south Lebanon last year and calling on Israel to pay 1.7
million U.S. dollars in damages.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz was quoted by the
state-run Lebanon Radio as saying that the results of Friday's
vote in favor of the resolution was a victory in the "U.N.'s
battle to keep its credibility."
</P>
<P>
The vote confirmed an unprecedented motion in the assembly's
fifth committee which required Israel to finance the 1997-1998
budget of the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) because of
its culpability in the Qana massacre.
</P>
<P>
"What happened is not Lebanon's battle. It is the U.N.'s
battle to keep its credibility as a reference of right and
justice in the world. The Lebanese cause, which was expressed
through the Qana massacre, is finally linked with other
nations," Boueiz said.
</P>
<P>
Alluding to pressure exerted by the United States prior to
the vote to save Israel from being held responsibility, Boueiz
said the decision would portray a clear message not only by
condemning the Qana massacre, but also by condemning practices
inside the United Nations which "were and are still threatening
the world organization's cause."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister expressed the hope that the U.N. Security
Council would follow the general assembly to approve a similar
resolution.
</P>
<P>
He stressed a necessity for the U.N. to work on implementing
its decision in order to sustain its credibility.
</P>
<P>
"In this way countries would not be forced to claim their
rights by force and would not have to suffer from violence," he
said.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 Lebanese civilians taking refuge in the Qana
camp were killed when Israeli artillery shelled it on April 18,
1996, during Israel's "Grapes of Wrath" operation against
Lebanese guerrillas in south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
