<HEADLINE> Greene Runs 10th Fastest Time in History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Maurice Greene won the title in
9.90 seconds to equal the 10th fastest time ever run on Friday at
the U.S. Athletics Championships in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
"It's time for an American to step up," Greene was quoted as
saying after his victory. He also warned for the world's elite
sprinters: watch out.
</P>
<P>
Americans have not won a championship 100-meter title since
Carl Lewis's 1991 world title. Canadian Donovan Bailey holds the
world record at 9.84 seconds.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's time for someone to stand up, and I'll do that to
help put American sprinting back where it's supposed to be,"
Greene said.
</P>
<P>
Marion Jones, the women's sensation of the USA Track and Field
Championships, ran her third straight strong race, winning the
100-meter dash, while two-time Olympic gold medalist Gail Devers
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
Jones, who cloced 10.98 and 10.92 at Indiana University Track
and Field Stadium with the year's two-fastest times in Thursday
night's preliminaries and semifinals, won her first national title
in 10.97 in a race run into a headwind.
</P>
<P>
Jones had shown her potential in high school, when as a
16-year-old junior, she finished fifth in the 100 and fourth in
the 200 at the 1992 Olympic trials, reports said reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Devers, the 1993 world champion and two-time Olympic gold
medalist, pulled out the final, claiming a sore right calf muscle.
</P>
<P>
If the International Amateur Athletic Federation decides to add
"wild card" entries for the World Championships, Devers could
possibly participate, along with other world champions and Olympic
gold medalists such as Michael Johnson and Dan O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
Devers had clocked 10.99 seconds in a preliminary race on
Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
