<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Calls off Scheduled Visit to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu has canceled his U.S. trip scheduled for late June,
according to the state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted an official statement issued by the Prime
Minister's Office Friday as saying that Netanyahu decided to cancel
the visit because he wants to stay at home to deal with the highly
controversial Conversion Bill which is causing serious problems
affecting Israel's relations with millions of conservative and
reformist Jews in Diaspora.
</P>
<P>
However, the commercial Channel 2 of the state-run Israel
Television reported that the real reason is that the premier
does not want to meet with U.S. President Bill Clinton at a low
point in the Arab-Israeli peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has made no secret that it is not
satisfied with the little progress made in the Middle East peace
talks since the rightwing Likud government took office a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madelein Albright has repeatedly
declared that she will not visit the region unless the Israelis
and Palestinians make up their minds to adopt difficult
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Jordanian King Hussein
and other Arab leaders have called on Clinton to put pressure on
Netanyahu in order to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu originally planned to attend a U.N. environmental
conference in New York and then go for a summit with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy will represent Israel in
Netanyahu's place at the U.N. meeting instead, said the radio.
</P>
<P>
The peace negotiations between the Palestinians and Israelis
broke off three months ago when Israel began construction of the
Har Homa Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians refused to resume the talks unless Israel
agreed to halt the project and other construction activities in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The latest mediation efforts by Egyptian envoy Osama el-Baz to
the Jewish state and the Palestinian self-rule areas this week
reportedly made no progress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
