<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Break-ins, Robberies on Rise in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 14 (Xinhua) -- With recent consecutive reports
on new cases, break-ins and robberies in the residential areas of
the well-to-dos in Singapore appeared to be on the rise and more
foreigners fell victim to the knife-point of the robbers.
</P>
<P>
In the western part of Singapore, an island state with an area
of more than 600 square kilometers, at least five robberies and
nine break-ins were reported between January and May this year,
the Straits Times said today, citing police figures.
</P>
<P>
Early Monday morning, a British couple, Andrew Davis and wife,
Lesley, were tied up with a telephone line and threatened with
knives taken from their kitchen by the masked burglars, one of
whom wore only underwear. The robbers took away more than 10,000
U.S. dollars worth of jewelry, equipment and cash.
</P>
<P>
One hour later at around 2:50 AM, Clarence Chandran, a visiting
senior executive of the Canadian telecommunication giant Northern
Telecom, was stabbed during a robbery at a Bukit Timah bungalow,
not too far away from the site of the earlier case. About 12,000
U.S. dollars worth of jewelry and his credit cards were taken
away.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Jurong Police Division, which is in charge
of the western area, was quoted as saying seven of the 14 cases
had been solved. He said most of the targets were private
residences, but he could not comment on whether the recent
break-ins were the work of a single gang of robbers.
</P>
<P>
Victims, however, said there had been a striking similarity in
the way the robbers worked in several of the cases: They struck in
the early hours of the morning; they were armed with knives taken
from the kitchens of the homes they broke into; and they tied up
their victims with electrical cord or telephone wire.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the robbers used their victims' T-shirts or other
clothing to mask themselves, and several of the victims noted that
one or more of the robbers had only underwear on.
</P>
<P>
The police spokesman said the police had little background
information on the robbers who move in and out of Singapore, often
illegally, and who don't remain anywhere for long while in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Last year, there were a total of 1,737 break-ins reported and
this was said to be the lowest figure in 19 years. Meanwhile, the
total of 768 robberies reported last year were said to be the
lowest level recorded in 38 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
