<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil is ranked 68th among the 175 countries
worldwide rated by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
in its annual report on human development.
</P>
<P>
Judged on life expectancy at birth, schooling and per capita
income, Brazil maintains itself among countries considered to have
an "average human development," according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Poverty increased in Latin America and the Caribbean, a region
where 110 million people, 24 percent of the region's population,
live with less than a dollar a day, said the U.N. agency.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's imports were valued at 3.198 billion
dollars in the first four months of the year, 23.3 percent up from
the 1.593 billion dollars registered in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
As the rise was across all sectors, said the Central Statistics
and Information Bureau, 71.6 percent of the imports came from the
United States, Colombia, Germany, Brazil, Japan, Italy and France.
</P>
<P>
Imports from the United States were worth 1.508 billion
dollars, a 30.1 percent increase over the 1.159 billion dollars
registered between January and April of 1996.
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Cuba's gross domestic product (GDP) is expected to
grow 4 percent this year, Alfonso Casanova, vice minister of
economy and planning told a meeting here.
</P>
<P>
Casanova discussed the outlook of the Cuban economy before some
300 delegates from 18 countries to the 6th Latin American and the
Caribbean Economists Association Congress.
</P>
<P>
He noted that 1997 started for Cuba with exceptional financial
difficulties, a circumstance worsened by a deterioration in the
international rate of exchange.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil received 6 billion dollars in foreign
investments in the first five months of 1997, a 76.8 percent rise
over the same period of 1996, said the Central Bank of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
This has been a big increase of direct foreign investments
since 1994, when the "Plan Real" was implemented to help recover
the economy and control the inflation, said the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico had a trade surplus of 1.564 billion
dollars during the first four months of this year, said the
Finance and Public Credit Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The value of Mexico's exports during the four months was 34.189
billion dollars, a 14.8 percent increase over the same period of
1996, said the ministry in a communique.
</P>
<P>
Total exports of goods in April rose to 9.146 billion dollars,
15.6 percent more than those in the same month of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
