<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Lift Ban on Agro-Fishery Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will lift the ban on
import of major agricultural, livestock and fishery products,
except rice and beef, from this July, according to the Ministry of
Finance and Economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry sources, under the settled Uruguay
Round of the trade negotiations on agricultural products, the
government will allow importers to freely introduce 56
agricultural, livestock and fishery goods, including pork,
chicken, natural honey, orange, mackerel and laver, from foreign
countries starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
The import of frozen beef and several kinds of beef byproducts will
also be permitted starting July 1, before the full liberalization of
beef imports in 2001.
</P>
<P>
With the deregulation, the nation's import-liberalization ratio
will rise to 99.9 percent for the nation's industries overall and to
99.6 percent for agricultural, livestock and fishery products.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the import of all products, except rice, will be
liberalized by 2001, the ministry officials said that the
rice-deregulation issue will be discussed at the Uruguay Round
negotiations in 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
