<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Russia-Belarus Parliamentary Assembly Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of a new joint
parliamentary assembly set up under a Union Treaty on integration
between Russia and Belarus ended today.
</P>
<P>
The session, held in the Belarussian town of Brest, ended with
the playing of the parliament's anthem, the national anthem of the
former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The Parliamentary Assembly of the Russia and
Belarus Community of Sovereign Republics was set up after Russia
and Belarus signed a treaty on integration on April 2, creating the
Community of Sovereign Republics (CSR). The assembly is made up of
an equal number of deputies from both countries.
</P>
<P>
Representatives at the two-day session called for wide-ranging
constructive dialogue between leaders, parliaments and the people
of the member states of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS) and other countries to jointly promote world peace and
international stability, the Russian media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The assembly, which has mainly only symbolic powers, approved
several documents, including an appeal to the parliament of the
CIS, the European Council and the parliament of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
The members noted that the signing of the Russia-Belarus
Union Charter by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his
Belarussian counterpart Alexander Lukashenko on May 23 reflects
the maturity of relations between the two countries and their will
to be further unified.
</P>
<P>
The charter conforms to the fundamental interests and
willingness of the two countries and the Russia-Belarus union to
create a new geopolitical entity on the Europe-Asia continent,
representatives said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
