<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Industrial Output Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Industrial production in Italy,
prompted by government incentives to the automobile sector, hiked
by 8.2 percent in April over the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The auto industry registered a 14.9 percent growth, the highest
among all industrial sectors, said Istat, the national statistics
institute, said in a report released today.
</P>
<P>
The industry's growth was the result of a government decision
earlier this year to subsidize sales of new cars to those who
remove used vehicles over 10 year old.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors that saw large rises in April were paper and
publishing (16.4 percent), transport (15.9), textile and clothing
(14.4), rubber and plastics (13.6).
</P>
<P>
Food production increased 9.2 percent, and that of power, water
and gas was up 8.9, Istat says.
</P>
<P>
A notable drop of 0.9 percent in output came from electrical
and optical machine and appliances.
</P>
<P>
Italy's industrial production for the whole year of 1996 fell
on average by 1.7 percent from the figure recorded in 1995, when a
5.4 percent rise was registered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
