<HEADLINE> Japan's GDP Grows in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Japan's economy grew 1.6 percent in
real terms in the first quarter of this year over the last quarter
of 1996, bringing real growth in gross domestic product (GDP)
during fiscal 1996 to a strong 3 percent, media reports here
said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Economic Planning Agency said Friday in a preliminary
report that GDP growth for the past fiscal year exceeded the
government's earlier growth prediction by 0.5 percentage points
and marked the largest jump in six years, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The annualized growth rate for the quarter was 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
GDP, which measures total annual output of goods and services,
is an indication of the state of a nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1.6 percent real growth for the quarter, 1.5 percent was
attributed to domestic demand and 0.1 percent to external demand.
</P>
<P>
Net exports of goods and services amounted to 3.46 trillion yen
(30.4 billion U.S. dollars) in the first quarter, up 10.3 percent
from the previous quarter, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
