<HEADLINE> Nepalese Complain About Oil Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Complaints have been heard all
over Nepal after a price hike in petroleum products came out
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
From motorbike and car owners to housewives, from cities to
villages, people from all walks of life are complaining about the
price hike, press reports here said today.
</P>
<P>
Some are worried that the rise in petroleum products may lead
to higher prices for other commodities.
</P>
<P>
Under the new price structure set by the Nepal Oil Corporation
(NOC), gas is now sold for 39 rupees per liter, up five rupees,
diesel for 17.5 rupees, up 3.5 rupees, and kerosene for 11 rupees,
up 1.5 rupees.
</P>
<P>
But NOC officials said they had no other choice because in the
past eight to nine months, the NOC has suffered a loss of 490
million rupees (about 8.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Nepalese Transport Entrepreneurs (FNTE) has
also criticized the NOC's move and put forth its own demand for a
price rise to the Ministry of Works and Transport.
</P>
<P>
"If the government fails to meet our demand, then we will hike
the price on our own," the FNTE said in a press release.  
</P>
</TEXT>
