<HEADLINE> Tamil Rebels Death Toll Rises in North Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of Tamil rebels
rose to 320 during their massive attack on military defense
positions in Vavuniya District in Sri Lanka's Northern Province,
the official Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 Tamil rebels attacked the military defense on
June 9 in an attempt to overrun the Army's field headquarters, but
government troops repulsed the attack, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Rebel transmissions confirmed Friday that more than 320 rebel
fighters had been killed during their abortive counterattack on
government troops. Meanwhile, 39 bodies of the troops killed in
action have been recovered and 12 officers and 86 soldiers injured
had been taken to hospital, it added.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the rebels' attack had been to disrupt the ongoing
military operation by government troops in the north of the island
country.
</P>
<P>
The government troops have been carrying out a major offensive
code-named "Jaya Sikuru" (Certain Victory) since May 13 with the
intention of recapturing 75 kilometers of road on the main highway
form Vavuniya to Jaffna through the rebel-held territory.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a war since 1983 for a
separate state in the north and east of the country.  
</P>
