<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's banana exports in April, 9.7 million
boxes each weighing 18.14 kilograms, or 40 pounds, was an 11.4
percent increase over the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, in the previous three months, the country's
banana exports dropped 20 percent to 21.4 million boxes, because
of cold temperatures registered at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Banana exports in the first three months of 1996 were 25.6
million boxes.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's catch for the production and export of fish
meal and fish oil dropped 20.8 percent during the first five
months of this year, compared to the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The five-month catch was 2,835,309 metric tons, versus the same
period of 1996's 3,580,015 tons. The drop is attributed to a ban
on the catch of yellow jack jurel in the country's center-south.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua ranks the world's 127th in terms of human
development, above Haiti, the poorest country in the Americas,
said a latest United Nations report.
</P>
<P>
Almost 2 million Nicaraguans, or 44 percent of the population,
survive with one U.S. dollar a day and 13.6 percent will not live
to 40, said the UN annual report on human development.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Private investments in Colombia's
infrastructure reached 2.2 billion dollars in 1996, a 31.3 percent
increase over 1995, said the country's National Council on
Economic and Social Policies.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 1.8 billion dollars was in mining and energy
sectors, a 40 percent growth, and 140 million dollars in
transportation, a 43.5 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Ecuador's foreign currency reserves, currently at a
high of 2.216 billion dollars, were some 220 million dollars more
than at the start of the year, said the country's Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The increase was the result of an "adequate" financial
operation of the Central Bank and the acceptance of the "exchange
auction" on the foreign exchange market, the bank said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The Central bank has been regulating the supply and demand of
dollars, a measure that some experts consider as a way to control
the exchange rate and prevent speculation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
