<HEADLINE> Thailand to Boost Measures Over Myanmar Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will beef up measures to
control 90,000 Myanmar refugees in northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from government agencies responsible for
security affairs agreed at a meeting on Thursday to enforce new
measures to control Myanmar refugees in Tak and Mae Hong Son
provinces to ensure that Thailand can shoulder this long-lasting
burden efficiently.
</P>
<P>
A report today quoted a Thai military source as saying that
under the new measures, the number of refugee camps in both
provinces will be cut from 16 to nine and all camps will be fenced
off.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Interior Ministry will transfer more officials to
oversee the refugee camps which are now being run by a large
number of volunteers, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Public Health Ministry officials will offer medical services to
the refugees and check if medicines provided by non-governmental
organizations are properly used by them.
</P>
<P>
The source said police and camp staff will prevent refugees
from engaging in business activities and working outside the
camps.  
</P>
</TEXT>
