<HEADLINE> Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, June 14 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade has been
maintaining a fast and sound growth since the 1980s, further
stablizing its place in world trade, according to Wu Yi, minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that with a double-digital growth for years running,
China's foreign trade constituted an important part in China's
national economy. "It has become a nexus between the country's
economy and economies worldwide and promoted optimized allocation
of resources," she said.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade growth averaged 16.6 percent between 1979
and 1995, some eight percentage points higher than the world's
average, she added.
</P>
<P>
Also, the trade volume of the country to the world's total has
increased from 0.78 percent in 1978 to three percent in 1996. For
five years in succession after 1992, China has been the world's
11th largest trader, "contributing to the development of overall
trade growth," she said. "Now it can be said that China's foreign
trade growth gives a new impetus to world economic growth," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
