<HEADLINE> Shanghai People Invest More in Securities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Saving money in banks is no longer
the first choice of Shanghai residents, who are targeting more of
their earnings at the securities market and foreign exchange
market.
</P>
<P>
A local survey by the Shanghai branch of the People's Bank of
China, the central bank, showed that the growth of bank savings
deposits has been slowing down, together with a smaller increase
in their earnings.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai people are turning to a good combination of safety,
yields, and liquidity in money management, and more of them
distribute their money in a wider range of investment choices,
instead of the traditional way of relying solely on bank savings,
according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
About 45 percent of the respondents said they would choose to
buy securities if the interest rates of savings deposits remain
unchanged, as against the 32 percent who would continue to take
bank savings as the first choice, the survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
