<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000-year-old Mint Found In Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Remains of a mint dating back to the
Western Han Dynasty (206 BC-24 AD) has been found in Huxian county
in northwest China's Shaanxi province.
</P>
<P>
Coins and moulds with inscriptions of date in the reign of
Emperor Wudi (140-86 BC) and a dozen different coins and moulds
from the Xin Dynasty (24-25) have been unearthed from the site,
suggesting that the mint was operational for more than a century,
Chinese archaeologists say.
</P>
<P>
They say that the find will contribute to the study of monetary
history and the development of coining technology.
</P>
<P>
The site, measuring 1500 m by 600 m, was divided into sections
of mould-making, smelting and coining, pottery-making, and that to
collected used moulds.
</P>
<P>
Also found at the site were quality tile ends and remains of
large building foundation made of rammed earth, traces of an
administrative agency for coin-making, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
According to the experts, the site was probably where Qin Shi
Huang, China's first unifier who established the Qin Dynasty
(221-206 BC), smelt all weapons confiscated from the six other
states that he conquered.
</P>
<P>
It became a mint after Emperor Wudi of the Western Han Dynasty
re-took the coin-making power into the imperial court. In 118 BC,
the mint created coins bearing Chinese characters of "Wu Zhu"
(five zhu, one zhu equals 2.09 g).
</P>
<P>
Coins bearing "Wu Zhu" were also coined in later dynasties,
though their weight and size were different. Wu Zhu coins were the
largest in number and longest circulated money in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
Wang Mang, a minister of the Western Han Dynasty who later
seized the power and set up the short-lived Xin Dynasty, continued
using the mint and created more than 20 different coins, a result
of his monetary reform.
</P>
<P>
The coins he made, such as knife-shaped ones and those bearing
Chinese characters of "Da Quan" (large spring), have long been
regarded as unique and exquisite and are sought after by scholars
and collectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Killed by Flood in Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Five soldiers and a woman died
when the military vehicle they were riding in was swept by flood
in the 3rd region of Chile, the Defense Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred Wednesday near Las Vinitas, where troops
had been sent to rescue three members of a family who had been
trapped by floods caused by heavy rains, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The vehicle carrying the soldiers and those rescued was swiped
away by the current of the Copiapo River, which unexpectedly
increased in force, when it entered the Copiapo community.
</P>
<P>
A woman, a child, another soldier and two non-commissioned
officers survived the accident.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains in recent days have affected 5,257 persons in the
3rd and 12th regions, said the National Emergency Office of the
Chilean Interior Ministry. 
</P>
