<HEADLINE> EximBank Big Insurer In China's Export Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Export and Import Bank of
China is expected to provide credit insurance to more than two
billion yuan's worth of exports in 2000, according to a senior
bank official.
</P>
<P>
The insured value will grow at an annual rate of more than 60
percent over the next four years, said Dong Zhiguang, chairman of
the board of directors of the EximBank.
</P>
<P>
"The rapid expansion of our export credit insurance business
protected China's foreign trade companies against the foreign
exchange rates fluctuations and provided firm support for our
enterprises to tap the world market," said Dong Zhiguang.
</P>
<P>
Dong also said his bank would continue to develop the financial
instrument for other export goods for better support to the
nation's foreign trade sector.
</P>
<P>
Insurance service for overseas investment by Chinese
enterprises is also expected to start soon, said Dong.
</P>
<P>
Already a major provider of export credit of machinery
products, the EximBank provided export credit insurance for 600
million yuan's worth of goods last year, nearly triple the value
in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The EximBank is already the agent bank of 113 overseas banks
and has set up branches or representative offices in 83 countries
and regions.  
