<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Nickel-Hydrogen Battery Production Line Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 14 (Xinhua) -- China's first nickel-hydrogen
battery production line recently became operational in Shenyang,
capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
At a cost of 300 million yuan, the first-phase of the project
is designed to be capable of producing 30 million nickel-hydrogen
batteries and 300 tons of hydrogen-rich alloying powder.
</P>
<P>
Local experts said the new product could be widely used in
telecom devices, computers, home electric appliances or electric
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Zhongliao Sanpu Battery Co. Ltd., one of the key local battery
producers, introduced foreign expertise for the project.
</P>
<P>
Also, the company has developed three categories of batteries
in 13 varieties.
</P>
<P>
The target set by the company this year is to produce 10
million batteries, 200 tons of alloying powder and 100,000
batteries for mobile phones, with a combined industrial output
value of 120 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the company predicted that the company is to
reach the goal to produce 100,000 batteries a day in July,
1998. 
