<HEADLINE> People Determined to Save "Mother River" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 14 (Xinhua) -- More than one million people in
northeast China's Liaoning province recently signed on a cloth
piece to show their determination to work together to save their
seriously polluted "mother river".
</P>
<P>
Sources said that with rapid economic development in the
region, the 1,430-kilometer-long Liaohe River had to receive 1.5
billion tons of waste water each year.
</P>
<P>
A recently-issued communique on national environmental quality
conditions reported that among China's seven biggest rivers, the
Liaohe River had suffered most serious pollution.
</P>
<P>
"The State Council has attached great importance to the
treatment of pollution in the region, and the river was listed
number one that should be well treated," said a provincial
official.
</P>
<P>
On June 5 of the World Environment Day, the province launched a
move called "Saving the Mother River means to save ourselves",
which received great response from local residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
