<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Criticizes Lack of Environmental Commitment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Industrialized countries have
failed to honor the environmental commitments they made at the
Earth Summit in 1992, a senior Cuban official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Elena Simeon, Cuba's Science, Technology and Environment
Minister, made the denouncement before leaving for New York, the
United States, for a United Nations special session on environment.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, Simeon said, it was clearly established at the
Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, that the industrialized
world owes an ecological debt to the world's poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
The indebtedness stems from the fact that industrialized
countries are the biggest polluters of the planet, she said.
</P>
<P>
However, only Sweden, Norway, the Netherlands and Denmark have
fulfilled the commitment of delivering 0.7 percent of their gross
domestic product (GDP) as an assistance to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, studies have shown that nearly 125 billion
U.S. dollars will be needed each year to undo the serious
environmental damage caused to mankind.
</P>
<P>
Simeon said the Cuban government defends the agreements signed
at the 1992 summit meeting and supports the unity of the
developing world behind the objectives of these documents.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. special committee will hold a special session on
environment issues on June 23-27, and preparatory meetings at the
level of experts and ministers will begin next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
