<HEADLINE> Philippine Bank Cuts Borrowing, Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
has reduced further its overnight borrowing and lending rates by 1
percent in line with its goal of bringing down its short-term
rates to normal levels.
</P>
<P>
The central bank on Friday lowered its overnight borrowing rate
from 14 to 13 percent and its lending rate from 16 to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rates indicate the levels at which the monetary authorities
are willing to borrow from or lend to commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The further cut in the borrowing and lending rates was brought
by the relative stability of the foreign exchange market this
month.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's overnight borrowing rate was at 11 percent
before it was raised to 20 percent at the height of a speculative
attack on the country's currency, the peso, last month.
</P>
<P>
Central bank officials said earlier that the move to jack up
its overnight rates was just a temporary measure specifically
aimed at quashing the speculative attack against the Philippine
currency.
</P>
<P>
The peso Friday strengthened to 26.382 against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is expected to further slash its rates to
levels prior to the speculative attacks last month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
