<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Opposition to NATO Expansion Unchanged: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Reacting to U.S. President Bill
Clinton's announcement on Thursday that he was backing Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic to join NATO in its first wave of
expansion, Russia today reiterated its opposition to the
enlargement of the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
"The principle position of Moscow to oppose the eastward
expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) remains
unchanged," a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry told the Interfax
news agency today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Russia still maintains that NATO's
eastward expansion is a big mistake by the West and Russia will
pay close attention to the development of the situation and will
take that into consideration when drafting policies.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated Russia's proposal to set up a structure for
European security in the 21 century, comprising all European
nations within the framework of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation of Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Russia and NATO signed an agreement defining their
relationship, cooperation and security matters in Paris on May 27,
a deal seen as paving the way for NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the member states of the western military alliance
will hold a summit in Madrid next month to finalize the list of
new NATO members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
