<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emergency Meeting to Study El Nino Phenomenon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Pacific Permanent
Commission (SPPC), made up of Colombia, Chile, Ecuador and Peru,
has called for an emergency meeting on the El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
This was announced today here by SPPC secretary general Nicolas
Roncagliolo Higueras, who said the meeting will be held July 2 to
4 in Lima.
</P>
<P>
Roncagliolo said at a press conference here that oceanic and
atmospheric conditions have been registered since March in front
of the South American coasts, which correspond to the development
stages of El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
There were anomalies, he said, in the temperature of the
surface of the seas and even bigger anomalies in the coastal zones
of the SPPC member countries.
</P>
<P>
Roncagliolo said the emergency meeting is going to be attended
by scientists of the member countries, and it aims at preparing a
regional diagnostic of the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also establish a mechanism for the following
of the evolution of the phenomenon and its effects, in addition to
recommending measures to be taken.
</P>
<P>
The SPPC, with headquarters in Lima, is a regional organization
created in 1952 to coordinate the maritime policies of its member
countries, with special emphasis on the conservation and the
rational use of maritime resources.
</P>
<P>
The recurrence of the El Nino phenomenon caused the SPPC to
establish the regional program for the study of the El Nino
phenomenon with the purpose of improving the region's scientific
capability to forecast and confirm the presence of the
phenomenon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Registration of Voters Starts in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The general registration of voters
for next year's local and general elections started across the
Philippines today, almost a year before the polling day.
</P>
<P>
About 40 million Filipinos are expected to be registered as
voters today, tomorrow and on June 21-22, according to the
country's Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
During the four days, registration starts at 07:00 and ends at
17:00 at 170,000 centers nationwide, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
However, the registration will continue on June 23 and will not
conclude until January 11, 1998, or 120 days before the elections
of the president, vice president, parliamentarians and local
officials. Voters who fail to register during the four-day general
listing are allowed to file registration applications with local
elections officers later.
</P>
<P>
But the Election Commission is calling on voters to register
soon to make the registration process smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine Constitution, a qualified voter must have
reached the age of 18, and resided in the country for at least a
year before the elections and at least six months in the village
where he intends to vote.
</P>
<P>
Although the registration of voters has begun, both the ruling
party and opposition parties have not chosen their presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
The country's Election Law provides that the official campaign
period does not begin earlier than 90 days before the day of the
election, or on February 9,1998, while the choice of presidential
candidates cannot be announced by their respective parties,
groups, or coalition earlier than 165 days before the May 19
election, or on November 26, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
