<DOCNO> XIE19970614.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oklahoma Bombing Convict Condemned to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The federal jury in Denver,
Colorado, that found Timothy McVeigh guilty of bombing an Oklahoma
City federal building in 1995 in the worst terrorist attack in
U.S. history, today condemned him to die.
</P>
<P>
McVeigh was convicted of three counts of conspiring to blow up
the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building and eight counts of
murdering the eight federal agents who died in the blast that
killed 160 other people and injured hundreds.
</P>
<P>
The jury of seven men and five women heard more than two months
of testimony and deliberated four days before convicting McVeigh.
It took more than 10 hours for them to make the decision,
according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
The state of Oklahoma has said it still intends to try the
29-year-old McVeigh in the 160 other deaths, which included
children at a day care center in the federal building.
</P>
<P>
A second suspect in the case, Terry Nichols, is awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
In Oklahoma City, along the fence where the bombed-out federal
building once stood, cheers erupted from people who had gathered
to learn McVeigh's fate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
