<HEADLINE> Bullish Auction Mart of Arts In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shanghai, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Sales of artistic works in
Shanghai have been brisk this year. In this month alone,
collectors in the metropolis have witnessed a dozen satisfactory
auctions.
</P>
<P>
Leading local auction houses, such as the Shanghai Auction
Mart, Duoyunxuan Art Auction Co., Shanghai Dekang Art Auction Co.,
and Shanghai International Auction Co. Ltd. have all achieved
transaction records.
</P>
<P>
Dekang, for example, held a two-day auction attracting 500
bidders and relieving them of 17 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
One lot which aroused much interest was an oil painting of a
peasant woman by a female Chinese artist, Kang Jinmei. The work,
done in the early 1980s, eventually fetched half a million yuan
after 20 rounds of bidding. It is the highest price paid for an
artistic work by a Chinese female artist.
</P>
<P>
The sale of the Kang Jinmei canvas highlights the interest in
contemporary Chinese oil painting, which was generally neglected
in previous auctions. Eighty-five percent of the 40 oils offered
by the Shanghai International Auction Co. were sold.
</P>
<P>
However, traditional works of art still command the greatest
interest in the auction rooms. In the most successful sale, held
by Duoyunxuan, 35.5 million-yuan was spent by bidders, and 83
percent of the Chinese paintings and calligraphic works found new
owners.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that results from the auction houses in Shanghai
show the current health of art collecting, a far cry from the
depression it experienced soon after its appearance for the first
time in China in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
