<HEADLINE> Greece Takes Measures to Combat Excessive Use of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Greek cabinet today decided to
take measures to combat the overuse of pharmaceuticals and
prescriptions in order to offer the public cheap medicine and save
money for health care funds.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the cabinet meeting, Greek Health Minister
Costas Geitonas said that his country was among the top consumers
of pharmaceuticals, especially antibiotics, and spending had
increased to 584 billion drachmas (about 22.5 billion U.S.
dollars) from 87 billion drachmas (about 335 million dollars) in
1987.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the upsurge in spending to the overuse of
prescriptions, higher prices and new expensive medicines replacing
traditional products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
