<HEADLINE> US Expresses Concerns Over Turkey's Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today expressed concerns over Turkey's
increasing tension between the government and the military.
</P>
<P>
"On the issue of Turkey, we obviously are watching and have
been watching the situation very carefully," Albright told
reporters ahead of a meeting with Latvian Foreign Minister Valdis
Birkavs.
</P>
<P>
She said the United States supported the continuation of
Turkey's secular system of government. She also said any changes
in Turkey should be "with no extra-constitutional approach."
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said Turkey was in a
"very difficult time." "Turkey has been for many months now in the
midst of a national debate about the nature of its political order
and about the role of Islam in a secular society," he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey military officials have recently warned of the threat of
growing Islamist activism in the country, which they say is aimed
at making Turkey into an Islamic state, and have pledged to use
force if necessary to preserve the secular system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
