<HEADLINE> US Engaging in "Telephone Diplomacy" in Mideast: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today it
was engaging in "telephone diplomacy" concerning the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is denying that it had been
sidelined in the peace process as Egypt stepped in to mediate,
aimed at reviving the stalled peace talks between the Palestinians
and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
"We're right in the middle of it," State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns told reporters. He said Washington was in direct
contact with officials from Israel, the Palestinian Authority,
Jordan and Egypt through what he called "telephone diplomacy."
</P>
<P>
He said Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yassir Arafat had "very nice meetings" Thursday
with Egyptian presidential envoy Osama al-Baz.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has stepped in to mediate after U.S. efforts to get the
Israelis and Palestinians back to the negotiating table fell flat.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the Palestinians and Israelis suspended in March,
as Israel started constructions of a new Jewish neighborhood in
Arab East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as the capital of
a future state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
