<HEADLINE> France to Withdraw Troops From Congo From Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- France will start withdrawing its
1,250 troops from the Congo Republic from 1600 GMT Sunday, after
completing the Pelican Operation aimed at evacuating foreigners,
the French Foreign Ministry announced today.
</P>
<P>
French troops joining the Pelican Operation, which began on
June 7, will start its "disengagement aimed at a total
withdrawal," said the Foreign Ministry in a communique.
</P>
<P>
French troops have evacuated a total of 4,770 foreigners,
including 1,350 French nationals, over the past six days,
according to the French military.
</P>
<P>
The commander of the French troops in the Congo, General Rene
Landrin, today asked the Air Africa air company to help withdraw
French soldiers, and the latter agreed.
</P>
<P>
France said today that it would not intervene in the Congo
conflict, which began on June 5 between government troops and the
militiamen of former President Denis Sassou N'Guesso.
</P>
<P>
Fighting reportedly calmed down today in Brazzaville and the
national mediation committee headed by the mayor of Brazzaville,
Bernard Kolelas, has presented a seven-point peace plan to bring
back peace to the capital.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, representatives of the two warring sides could meet
Saturday in Libreville, Gabon, for primary peace talks aimed at
reconciliation. 
</P>
