<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government Announces New Inflation Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The British Labor government has
been accused of softening its anti-inflation stance after
Chancellor Gordeon Brown announced the new inflation target
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While setting a long-term target of 2.5 percent inflation, the
chancellor left room for it to fluctuate within 1 percent either
side.
</P>
<P>
Justifying the new target, Brown said, "Any economy at some
point can suffer from external events or temporary difficulties,
often beyond its control."
</P>
<P>
In his speech at a dinner Thursday night, Eddie George,
governor of the Bank of England, expressed his approval of the
decision to abandon the old target for inflation of "2.5 percent
or less" set by former Chancellor Kenneth Clarke.
</P>
<P>
However, George made no reference to the fact that he would be
required to write an explanatory letter to the chancellor if
inflation rose beyond 3.5 percent or falls below 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to George to explain the new system of open
letters, Brown wrote, "The actual inflation rate will on occasions
depart from its target as a result of shocks and disturbances."
</P>
<P>
George also dismissed suggestions that the bank would be
over-zealous in its pursuit of low inflation, claiming that the
intention was "to aim consistently at 2.5 percent as a mid-point."
</P>
<P>
However, most City economists thought the new target was not as
tough as the previous "2.5 percent or less."
</P>
<P>
"It is a slight dilution of the existing position. I'm a bit
disappointed," said Geoffrey Dicks, chief UK economist at Natwest
Markets.
</P>
<P>
"The Bank of England used to see 2.5 percent as an upper limit
and were aiming for something less. This is a looser target," said
Jonathan Loynes at HSBC Markets.
</P>
<P>
Former Chancellor Kenneth Clarke claimed that Brown had relaxed
the 2.5 percent target as a direct result of the Labor
government's decision immediately upon coming into power last
month to give the Bank of England operational independence for
setting interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Clarke claimed that Brown was concerned that the bank governor
would "over-compensate" with higher interest rates in order to be
sure of meeting the chancellor's inflation target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
